<p align="center"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">PART I</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="Business"><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1. Business</font></b></a></p>



<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ExpressJet Holdings, Inc.
(&ldquo;Holdings&rdquo;) has strategic investments in the air transportation sector.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of the issued
and outstanding shares of stock of XJT Holdings, Inc., the sole owner of the issued and outstanding shares of common stock of
ExpressJet Airlines, Inc. (&ldquo;Airlines&rdquo;), which operates as Continental Express.&nbsp; Holdings a<font color="black">lso
invests in other entities that permit it to leverage the management experience, efficiencies and economies of scale present in its
subsidiaries.&nbsp; Holdings and its wholly owned subsidiaries are collectively referred to in this report as
&ldquo;ExpressJet,&rdquo; &ldquo;we&rdquo; and &ldquo;us&rdquo; except as otherwise noted.</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our website address is
<i>www.expressjet.com</i>.&nbsp; In addition to other information, you may view the following materials on our website, free of
charge:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="653">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our reports and other filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission ("SEC"), which are
available as soon as reasonably practicable after we file them with, or furnish them to, the SEC;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the Corporate Governance Guidelines adopted by our board of directors establishing the general
policies by which the board operates;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Stockholders may print a copy of
any of the foregoing materials from our website or may request a copy from the Secretary of the company by writing to the address
on the cover of this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As described in the Principles of
Conduct, we have established means for our employees to report concerns of questionable accounting, auditing and other business
practices to our Director of Internal Audit and to the Corporate Compliance Officer.&nbsp; One way for them to do this is through
the following email address: <i>xjtinternalaudit@expressjet.com.&nbsp;</i> Persons desiring to communicate with the independent
members of our board of directors may also do so through this address.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On May 11, 2005, our Chief
Executive Officer provided his annual certification to the New York Stock Exchange ("NYSE") that he was not aware of any violation
by the company of the NYSE's corporate governance listing standards.&nbsp; In addition, our Chief Executive Officer and our Chief
Financial Officer have made the certifications required under Section 302 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, which are included as exhibits
to this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="fwdst"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Forward-Looking Statements</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This report contains
forward-looking statements.&nbsp; Statements in the "Business," "Properties" and "Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial
Condition and Results of Operation" sections of this report, together with other statements including words such as "believes,"
"intends," "plans," "anticipates, &ldquo;estimates," "projects," "expects" or similar expressions represent forward-looking
statements that are based on management's expectations in light of facts known by management on the date this report was filed with
the SEC.&nbsp; Specifically, statements regarding our future results of operations, operating costs, business prospects, growth and
capital expenditures, including plans with respect to our fleet, are forward-looking statements.&nbsp; These statements reflect our
plans and assumptions about future events and are subject to uncertainties, many of which are outside our control.&nbsp; Important
factors that could cause actual results to differ materially from the expectations expressed or implied in the forward-looking
statements include known and unknown risks.&nbsp; Some of the known risks that could significantly impact our revenues, operating
results and capacity include, but are not limited to: our ability to identify and execute income-generating arrangements for the 69
aircraft that Continental Airlines, Inc. (&ldquo;Continental&rdquo;) intends to withdraw from its capacity purchase agreement with
us; our dependence on our capacity purchase agreement with Continental; our dependence on Continental&rsquo;s airport, passenger
and infrastructure services; our dependence on Continental's financial and operational stability; our aircraft and facility leases
or subleases with</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Continental; our ability to implement our diversification strategy; certain tax matters; flight
disruptions as a result of operational matters; regulatory developments and costs, including the costs and other effects of
enhanced security measures and other possible regulatory requirements; and competition and industry conditions.&nbsp; For further
discussions of these risks, please see "Item 1A - Risk Factors" beginning on page 18.&nbsp; The statements in this report are made
as of February 27, 2006, and the events described in the forward-looking statements might not occur or might occur to a materially
different extent than described in this report.&nbsp; We undertake no duty to update or revise any of forward-looking statements,
whether as a result of new information, future events or otherwise.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><a name="ourcompany"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Our Company</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Holdings was incorporated in
Delaware in August 1996.&nbsp; We have strategic investments in the air transportation sector.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of
the issued and outstanding shares of stock of XJT Holdings, Inc., the sole stockholder of Airlines.&nbsp; Airlines is one of the
largest regional airlines in the world, based on available seat miles and number of regional jets, transporting passengers, cargo
and mail.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Airlines currently flies
exclusively on behalf of Continental pursuant to a capacity purchase agreement, and we receive substantially all of our revenue
under that agreement.&nbsp; We provide all of Continental's regional jet service out of New York/Newark, Houston and Cleveland, as
well as additional non-hub service.&nbsp; We believe our operations complement Continental's network.&nbsp; The capacity purchase
agreement covers all of our existing fleet and all of our remaining regional jets currently subject to firm aircraft order.&nbsp;
Although we began diversifying our operations in 2005, we remain economically dependent on Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On December 28, 2005, Continental
notified us of its intent to withdraw 69 aircraft from the capacity purchase agreement beginning in December 2006 and ending in
June 2007.&nbsp; Airlines currently leases or subleases all of its existing aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; The capacity purchase
agreement gives us up to nine months from the notice date to decide if we want to retain these aircraft.&nbsp; We are currently
evaluating whether or not we will do so.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of January 31, 2006, we
averaged 1,233 daily departures, offering scheduled passenger service to 152 cities in 40 states and the District of Columbia,
Guatemala, Mexico, Canada and the Caribbean.&nbsp; Our available seat miles have grown at a compounded annual rate of 20.4% from
4.7 billion in 2000 to 12.0 billion in 2005.&nbsp; We generated $1.6 billion of revenue and $98.0 million of net income for the
year ended December 31, 2005.&nbsp; Please refer to our consolidated financial statements included in this report for information
regarding our revenue and net income for each of the last three fiscal years and total assets as of the end of the last two
years.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2005, we announced that
our wholly owned subsidiary, ExpressJet Services, LLC (&ldquo;ExpressJet Services&rdquo;), and Airlines&rsquo; Training Services
division received third-party repair and training certificates, respectively, from the Federal Aviation Administration
(&ldquo;FAA&rdquo;). We anticipate that these certifications will allow us to generate additional revenues as we provide
third-party services to other airlines or aviation-related entities.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, we purchased
non-controlling interests in several entities in the air transportation sector during 2005.&nbsp; Please see Item 7.
&ldquo;Management&rsquo;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations &ndash; Executive Summary&rdquo;
and Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 1
&ndash; Summary of Accounting Policies&rdquo; for a description of our investments and the current accounting treatment related to
these entities.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After Continental&rsquo;s
ownership of our common stock fell below 10% in April 2005, we redeemed the sole share of our Special Voting Preferred Stock, which
was held by Continental. The redemption terminated Continental&rsquo;s right to elect a director to our board of directors.&nbsp;
Our capacity purchase agreement provided Continental the right to nominate a director to our board, but Continental relinquished
this right in October 2005.&nbsp; Continental currently owns less than 10% of our common stock and has indicated that it intends to
dispose of some or all of its remaining shares, subject to market conditions.&nbsp; We do not expect Continental's disposition of
our shares to have an adverse impact on our results of operations or financial position.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><a name="busstrategy"></a><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Business Strategy</font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We seek to enhance stockholder
value by providing the most efficient and reliable regional jet service.&nbsp; This service, coupled with opportunities arising
from the competencies we have developed, positions us as a leading provider of regional jet services.&nbsp; We believe that our
focus on cost and reliability has strengthened Continental and created opportunities for it beyond its network.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our commitment to reliability and
customer service has served Continental well.&nbsp; Continental&rsquo;s revenue experience demonstrates, in part, the utility of a
well run 50-seat aircraft operation within hub-and-spoke networks, particularly when the smaller aircraft are deployed to take full
advantage of their economic capabilities.&nbsp; Our newer Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica S.A. (&ldquo;Embraer&rdquo;) ERJ-145XR
aircraft enable Continental to serve more distant markets with demand for non-stop service to major metropolitan areas such as
Houston, New York/Newark, Los Angeles and Cleveland.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our cost structure, measured on a
per-seat mile basis, remains highly competitive and compares favorably to aircraft of much larger configurations.&nbsp; Comparisons
from publicly available data indicate that our direct operating costs on a per available seat mile basis for maintenance, flight
operations, fuel (at our capped rates under the capacity purchase agreement) and aircraft ownership reflect economics better than
many 100+ seat aircraft operated by major airlines.&nbsp; We believe that the capability and operating economics of our aircraft
will provide us strategic opportunities in the foreseeable future.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to our capacity
purchase agreement with Continental, we have begun exploring alternatives in order to enhance our stockholders' long-term value
through:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">seeking strategic opportunities for the 69 aircraft that Continental intends to withdraw from the
capacity purchase agreement;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">continuing to strengthen our balance sheet by lowering our debt obligations and increasing cash to
help position us for new opportunities;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">further diversifying our core business by making strategic investments in the air transportation
sector that will complement our current operations and leverage our operational expertise;</font></p>
</td>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><a name="cappurch"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements with Continental
Airlines</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<i>General.</i></font></b>&nbsp; We currently derive substantially all of our revenue from our capacity purchase agreement with
Continental.&nbsp; Under this agreement, Airlines operates flights on behalf of Continental as Continental Express.&nbsp;
Continental controls and is responsible for scheduling, pricing and managing seat inventories and is entitled to all revenue
associated with the operation of the aircraft.&nbsp; We also have various other agreements with Continental that govern our
relationship.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase
agreement, some marketing-related costs normally associated with operating an airline are borne by Continental.&nbsp; These costs
include:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><a name="OLE_LINK2"><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></a></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">reservations and
sales;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>

</td>
</tr>

</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On December 28, 2005, Continental
notified us that it would withdraw 69 aircraft from the capacity purchase agreement beginning in December 2006 and ending in June
2007.&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement gives us up to nine months from the notice date to decide if we want to retain the
aircraft.&nbsp; If we choose to retain the aircraft, the capacity purchase agreement contains a provision for the interest rate
implicit in calculating the scheduled lease payments we make to Continental to increase by 200 basis points.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<i>Payment.</i></font></b>&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase agreement, Airlines is entitled to payment for each block hour that
Continental schedules it to fly.&nbsp; Payment is based on a formula designed to provide Airlines with a target operating margin of
10% before taking into account variations in certain costs and expenses that are generally within our control.&nbsp; In accordance
with the capacity purchase agreement, the original cost components used in this formula remained in place until December 31, 2004,
after which, new rates began to be established annually using the same methodology.&nbsp; We have exposure for most labor costs and
some maintenance and general administrative expenses if the actual costs are higher than those reflected in Airlines&rsquo;
estimated block hour rates.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the terms of the capacity
purchase agreement, we began negotiations with Continental in the fall of 2005 to set the rates for 2006.&nbsp; Although the
agreement calls for rates to be set by November 1, we are still negotiating rates for 2006.&nbsp; As of this time, neither party
has requested arbitration to establish the rates.&nbsp; In the meantime, Continental is paying us at the rates applicable in
December 2005.&nbsp; Any agreement we reach on the 2006 rates will be applied retroactively to January 1, 2006.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<b><i>2001-2004</i></b><i>.</i>&nbsp; A reconciliation payment was made by Continental to Airlines, or by Airlines to Continental,
if the operating margin calculated, as described below (the "prevailing margin") was not between 8.5% and 11.5% in any fiscal
quarter.&nbsp; When the prevailing margin exceeded 11.5%, Airlines paid Continental an amount sufficient to reduce the margin to
11.5%.&nbsp; If the prevailing margin was less than 8.5%, Continental would have paid Airlines an amount sufficient to raise the
margin to 8.5%.&nbsp; During 2001 to 2004, the quarterly prevailing margins, before any reconciliation payments, were never below
8.5%.&nbsp; Certain items were excluded from the calculation of the prevailing margin, including:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">actual labor costs that differed from those reflected in Airlines&rsquo; block hour
rates;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">performance incentive payments, including payments from controllable cancellation performance
(cancellations other than weather or air traffic control cancellations);</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">litigation costs outside the normal course of business; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">other costs that were not included in Airlines&rsquo; block hour rates (or covered by any
adjustments to them) and were not reasonable and customary in the industry.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If these excluded costs were
higher than those anticipated in Airlines&rsquo; block hour rates, our operating margin could have been lower than 8.5% when taking
these costs into account, even after any reconciliation payment was made.&nbsp; Conversely, if these costs were lower than those
anticipated in Airlines&rsquo; block hour rates, our operating margin could have been higher than 11.5% when taking these costs
into account, even after any reconciliation payment was made.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />

respectively, and for 2001, the caps were 80.9 cents and 5.6 cents per gallon, respectively.&nbsp; If the fuel agreement with

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, to the extent that
Airlines&rsquo; rate of controllable cancellations (such as those due to maintenance or crew shortages) was lower than its
historical benchmarks, Airlines was entitled to incentive payments; conversely, Airlines would have had to pay Continental if its
controllable cancellations were above historical benchmarks.&nbsp; Because these incentive benchmarks were based on historical
five-year rolling averages of monthly controllable cancellations, lower controllable cancellations that resulted in higher
incentive payments in the near term reduced Airlines&rsquo; opportunity to earn incentive payments in the future.&nbsp; Also,
because Airlines used monthly rolling averages, its opportunity to earn these payments in any particular fiscal quarter was
affected by monthly variations in historical controllable cancellation rates.&nbsp; Airlines was also entitled to receive a small
per-passenger fee and incentive payments for certain on-time departure and baggage handling performance.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>2005 Rate Negotiation and
Amendment.</i></b>&nbsp; As part of the 2005 rate negotiation, we agreed to cap Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin at 10.0%.&nbsp;
Airlines also now includes previously unreconciled costs, as discussed previously, within the margin band, although it is not
reimbursed if these costs are higher and cause its prevailing margin to fall below the 8.5% margin floor.&nbsp; In addition,
Airlines is still entitled to receive incentive payments from Continental if its rate of controllable cancellations is lower than
its historical benchmark, but is not required to pay Continental a penalty for controllable cancellations unless the rate rises
above 0.5%.&nbsp; Airlines continues to receive a small per-passenger fee and incentive payments for certain on-time departure and
baggage handling performance.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The table below describes how
variations between Airlines&rsquo; actual costs and estimated costs, as determined in the block hour rates, have been treated under
the capacity purchase agreement since January 1, 2005.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
<tr>

extent actual costs differ from estimated costs.</p>

by either Continental or Airlines to the other so that this prevailing margin will be 8.5% or 10.0%, as applicable.&nbsp; If the
prevailing margin is less than 8.5% due to impact of certain costs, as described below, or if the prevailing margin is above 10.0%

</td>
<td valign="top">

lower of the actual costs or the agreed-upon caps of 66.0 cents per gallon and 5.2 cents per gallon, respectively, based on

</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Depreciation is reconciled for assets and capital projects accounted for in the capacity purchase
agreement or those approved by Continental outside of the capacity purchase agreement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">The prevailing margin used to calculate the reconciliation payment does not take into account
performance incentive payments, including payments from controllable cancellation performance, litigation costs above a historical
benchmark and other costs that are not included in the block hour rates (or covered by adjustments to them) or are not reasonable
and customary in the industry.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, the fully reconciled
costs and costs within the margin band under the capacity purchase agreement represented approximately 64% and 36% of total
operating costs, respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Certain costs that were
unreconciled under the capacity purchase agreement prior to 2005 now require Airlines to make a reconciliation payment to
Continental if the differences cause the prevailing margin to be greater than 10.0%.&nbsp; However, if the differences cause the
prevailing margin to be less than 8.5%, they remain unreconciled.&nbsp; These costs are:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">wages and salaries;
and&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">benefits not included in the table above.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>2006 Rate
Setting.</i></b>&nbsp; We negotiate with Continental to adjust the scheduled block hour rates annually as required under the
capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Because we have not agreed on the 2006 rates, Continental has agreed to continue paying Airlines
at the December 2005 rates until an agreement is reached.&nbsp; Any agreement to revise the current rate structure will be
retroactive to January 1, 2006.&nbsp; We cannot currently estimate what the 2006 rates will ultimately be.&nbsp; If we cannot agree
on the annual rates, the capacity purchase agreement allows either party to submit the matter to arbitration.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Scope of Agreement and
Exclusive Arrangement.</i></font></b>&nbsp; Subject to the aircraft withdrawal beginning in December 2006, the capacity purchase
agreement covers Airlines&rsquo; existing fleet of 266 aircraft, as well as the eight aircraft subject to firm orders at
December&nbsp;31, 2005 (three of which were delivered as of February 27, 2006).&nbsp; The agreement allows us to be
Continental&rsquo;s exclusive regional jet service provider at Newark&rsquo;s Liberty International, Houston&rsquo;s Bush
Intercontinental and Cleveland&rsquo;s Hopkins International airports through December 31, 2006.&nbsp; However, the capacity
purchase agreement permits up to 10 regional jet flights per day at each of these hubs by regional airlines that have arrangements
with Continental&rsquo;s airline code-share partners.&nbsp; This exclusivity would automatically and permanently terminate upon the
occurrence of a union-authorized strike.&nbsp; Otherwise, the agreement does not prohibit Continental from competing, or from
entering into agreements with other airlines that would compete, with routes we serve.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement
permits us to fly under our own code or on behalf of other airlines.&nbsp; However, there are provisions in the capacity purchase
agreement stating that:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at Continental&rsquo;s hubs, we may only fly for Continental;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any other airport where Continental, its subsidiaries and other regional jets operating under
Continental&rsquo;s code operate an average of more than 50 flights daily (although currently there are no such airports), we may
only fly for Continental; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">we cannot operate any of our aircraft subject to the capacity purchase agreement or use our
passenger-related airport facilities employed under the agreement for other carriers or for flights under our own code.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Because our license from
Continental to use the Continental Express name and other trademarks is non-exclusive, Continental is not prohibited from flying
its own planes or permitting other airlines to operate under the Continental Express name.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement
also provides that Continental has the right to withdraw a limited number of our regional jets covered by the agreement at any
time, provided that we receive at least 12&nbsp;months&rsquo; notice.&nbsp; On December 28, 2005, Continental gave us such a notice
with respect to 69 aircraft, the maximum number that it could currently withdraw from the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Under
the terms of the agreement, Continental cannot withdraw additional aircraft from the agreement until December 28, 2009 unless the
agreement is terminated early, which Continental can currently do with twelve months&rsquo; notice.&nbsp; With respect to the 69
aircraft released from the capacity purchase agreement, all of which were leased or subleased from Continental, we have the option
to:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">fly the released aircraft for other parties or under our own code, subject to our ability to obtain
facilities, such as gates and slots, and subject to any enforceable restrictions in the capacity purchase
agreement;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">sublease the aircraft to other parties; or</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">decline to fly these aircraft and cancel the related leases or subleases with
Continental.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If we elect to retain the
aircraft released from the capacity purchase agreement, the capacity purchase agreement contains a provision calling for the
interest rate implicit in calculating the scheduled lease payments to Continental to increase by 200 basis points.&nbsp; See
"&mdash;&nbsp;Aircraft Financing."&nbsp; If we elect not to retain these aircraft, the related leases or subleases between us and
Continental will be canceled, and Continental will take possession of the aircraft.&nbsp; In that event, Continental will be
responsible for all direct reasonable costs we incur in removing those aircraft from our fleet, including purchasing any excess
spare part inventory we may have related to these aircraft at net book value.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; So long as scheduled flights
under our capacity purchase agreement with Continental represent at least 50% of all our scheduled flights, or at least 200 of our
aircraft are covered by the agreement, we are required to allocate our crews, maintenance personnel, facilities and other resources
on a priority basis to scheduled flights under the agreement above all of our other flights and aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Code-Sharing and
Marketing.</i></font></b>&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement authorizes us to use Continental&rsquo;s two-letter flight
designator code (CO*) to identify Airlines&rsquo; flights in the central reservation system, to paint our aircraft with its
branding and to market and advertise our status as being a part of the Continental route system.&nbsp; The agreement also gives us
a non-exclusive license to fly under the Continental Express name.&nbsp; Passengers on Airlines&rsquo; scheduled flights under the
capacity purchase agreement can earn rewards under Continental&rsquo;s OnePass frequent flyer program.&nbsp; We do not pay fees
with respect to these services.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Aircraft
Financing.</i></font></b>&nbsp; Airlines currently leases or subleases all of its existing aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; As of
February 27, 2006, Airlines has 269 aircraft in its fleet and expects to take delivery of the remaining five aircraft under firm
orders by June 30, 2006 under the same financing terms involving Continental.&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase agreement,
Continental is required to purchase or lease from Embraer or its designee aircraft to be flown under the capacity purchase
agreement, participate in the financing and to lease or sublease these aircraft to us.&nbsp; Aircraft withdrawn from the capacity
purchase agreement become &ldquo;Uncovered Aircraft&rdquo; as defined in the agreement, and the capacity purchase agreement
contains a provision for the interest rate implicit in calculating the scheduled lease payments we make to Continental under the
relevant leases or subleases to automatically increase by 200 basis points.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The 100 ERJ-145XR aircraft that
we have options to purchase would also be Uncovered Aircraft since Continental has declined to include them under the capacity
purchase agreement.&nbsp; These option aircraft may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145 line of aircraft,
which include the ERJ-135, ERJ-145 and ERJ-145XR (&ldquo;ERJ-145 Family&rdquo;).&nbsp; While we retain the right to exercise these
options, we would have to finance our acquisition of these aircraft independently.&nbsp; We expect to notify Embraer of our
intentions regarding the first 25 option aircraft in March 2006.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental has the right to
terminate, at any time, any Uncovered Aircraft sublease and take possession of the aircraft so long as it provides us a replacement
aircraft and we can obtain financing reasonably satisfactory to us.&nbsp; If we do not obtain such financing, Continental cannot
require us to take the replacement aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental does not have any
obligation to finance, arrange to finance or participate in the financing of any aircraft acquired outside the capacity purchase
agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Airport Facilities, Slots
and Route Authorities</i>.</font></b>&nbsp; Most of the airport facilities that Airlines uses are leased from airport authorities
by Continental.&nbsp; Under Airlines&rsquo; master facility and ground handling agreement with Continental, Airlines is entitled to
use these facilities to fulfill its obligations under the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; However, we are generally not entitled
to use airport terminal facilities leased by Continental to service other carriers or operate flights under our own code without
Continental&rsquo;s approval.&nbsp; Further, we must use those facilities that are non-terminal facilities on a priority basis to
support the scheduled flights that Airlines flies on behalf of Continental so long as those flights constitute at least 50% of our
total scheduled flights or at least 200 of our aircraft are covered by the capacity purchase agreement.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In November 2003, Airlines&rsquo;
master facility and ground handling agreement with Continental was amended to clarify how airport terminal rent expenses would be
allocated to Airlines by Continental at the airport locations where Airlines operates.&nbsp; Under this amendment, all terminal
facility rents at Continental&rsquo;s hub airports are now borne by Continental, and Airlines pays for incremental rent at other
Continental-managed locations, unless Continental does not operate any scheduled aircraft there during a quarter.&nbsp; Airlines is
responsible for the rent expense at locations where Continental does not operate any aircraft.&nbsp; At locations Airlines manages,
rent is allocated between Continental and Airlines based on the number of each carrier&rsquo;s respective passengers.&nbsp; This
change reduced Airlines&rsquo; annual terminal facility rent costs by approximately $30 million in 2004 as compared to the rent
allocation method under its previous agreement with Continental.&nbsp; Since terminal facility rent is a fully reconciled cost, as
described above under "&mdash;2005 Rate Negotiation and Amendment," this change reduced our 2004 operating income by approximately
$3.3 million.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental is generally
responsible for all capital and start-up costs for airport terminal facilities at its hub airports and at any other facilities
where it elects to provide ground handling services to Airlines.&nbsp; If Continental elects to provide ground handling services at
any facility where Airlines previously did so, Continental will reimburse Airlines for most of the capital and start-up costs
Airlines incurred at that facility.&nbsp; We are generally responsible for capital and start-up costs associated with airport
terminal facilities where Airlines flies and any non-terminal facilities not regularly used by Continental.&nbsp; If Airlines exits
a market at the direction of Continental (and we do not re-enter that market within six months flying under our own code or that of
an airline other than Continental), Continental will reimburse us for certain losses incurred in connection with the closure of the
related facility. If the capacity purchase agreement is terminated, we may be required to vacate the terminal facilities (or all
facilities if the termination results from our material breach of the agreement) that are subleased to Airlines by Continental, and
to use commercially reasonable efforts to assign to Continental or its designee any of the facility leases in our name.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, there are provisions
in the capacity purchase agreement that require us to use commercially reasonable efforts to transfer, subject to applicable laws,
to Continental or its designee any of our airport take-off or landing slots, route authorities or other regulatory authorizations
used for Airlines&rsquo; scheduled flights under the agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Ground
Handling.</i></font></b><i></i>&nbsp; Airlines provides ground handling and other support services, including baggage handling,
station operations, ticketing, gate access and other passenger, aircraft and traffic servicing functions for Continental at several
of our airport locations.&nbsp; In exchange, Continental pays us an amount equal to Airlines&rsquo; incremental cost for providing
these services.&nbsp; Continental provides the same services for Airlines at its stations, including its hub airports.&nbsp; The
cost for these services is based on the number of scheduled aircraft and the rates stipulated in the capacity purchase
agreement.</p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Most Favored
Nations.</i></font></b>&nbsp; So long as Continental is our largest customer, if we enter into a capacity purchase or economically
similar agreement with another major airline (defined as any airline with annual revenues greater than $500 million, prior to
adjustment for inflation since 2000) to provide regional airline service for more than 10 aircraft on terms and conditions that
are, in the aggregate, less favorable to us than those in the capacity purchase agreement, the capacity purchase agreement has a
provision that may allow Continental to amend its agreement with us to conform to the terms and conditions of our new
agreement.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Change of
Control.</i></b>&nbsp; So long as Continental is our largest customer, if we experience a change of control without its consent,
there are provisions in the capacity purchase agreement that may cause Airlines&rsquo; block hour rates to be reduced by an amount
approximately equal to the operating margin built into those rates.&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase agreement, a change of
control of our company is defined as:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our merger or consolidation with a major airline, i.e., an airline other than Continental or its
subsidiaries that had more than $500 million of revenue, adjusted for inflation since 2000, (or, if we are the surviving entity, $1
billion of revenue) during the most recently completed fiscal year;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the acquisition by a major airline, or group of major airlines acting in concert, of more than 10%
of our capital stock or voting rights;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the acquisition by any other entity, or group of entities acting in concert, other than Continental
and its subsidiaries or passive investors, of more than 25% of our capital stock or voting rights, unless such entity or group
reduces its ownership to below this threshold within 30&nbsp;days of the acquisition;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>

subsidiaries) that had more than $1 billion of revenue during the most recently completed fiscal year;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our acquisition of airline assets that generated more than $500 million, prior to adjustment for
inflation since 2000, of revenue during the most recently completed fiscal year;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our merger or consolidation with another entity following which our stockholders own less than a
majority of the voting securities of the surviving entity;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the sale or other disposition of all or substantially all of our airline assets to a major
airline;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our liquidation or dissolution, in connection with which we cease operations as an air
carrier;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">a majority of our directors are neither our current directors or individuals nominated by a majority
of our board of directors; or</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our entering into definitive agreements relating to the foregoing matters.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Labor
Disruption.</i></b>&nbsp; Upon the occurrence of a union-authorized labor strike, the capacity purchase agreement provides
that:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Airlines will no longer have the right to be Continental&rsquo;s exclusive provider of regional jet
service at its hub airports in New York/Newark, Houston and Cleveland, regardless of the length of the strike;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Airlines will be compensated only for the flights it completes, and will not be compensated for any
controllable or uncontrollable cancellations regardless of its historical cancellation rates;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">on each of the 2nd, 15th, 30th, 45th, 60th and 75th days of the strike, Continental will be entitled
to terminate Airlines&rsquo; leases or subleases for, and take immediate possession of, up to 20 of Airlines&rsquo; aircraft
covered by the capacity purchase agreement, up to a maximum of 120 aircraft if the strike extends to the 75th day;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">we will be required to provide to Continental or its designee, for the duration of the strike and
180&nbsp;days thereafter and at market rates, first-priority access to all of our flight simulators, hangars, training and other
facilities and inventory to the extent necessary to enable Continental or its designee to operate any aircraft of which Continental
takes possession as a result of the strike;&nbsp;and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">if the strike continues for 90&nbsp;days or more, Continental is entitled to terminate the capacity
purchase agreement for cause, cancel Airlines&rsquo; leases or subleases and take immediate possession of all of the aircraft
covered by the capacity purchase agreement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, a labor disruption
other than a union-authorized strike may cause us to be in material breach of the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Under the
capacity purchase agreement, whenever Airlines fails to complete at least 90% of its aggregate scheduled flights (based on
available seat miles) in three consecutive calendar months or at least 75% of its aggregate scheduled flights (based on available
seat miles) in any 45-day period (in each case, excluding flights cancelled due to union-authorized labor strikes, weather, air
traffic control or non-carrier specific airworthiness directives or regulatory orders), we will be deemed to be in material breach
of the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; A labor disruption other than a union-authorized strike could cause Airlines to fail to
meet these completion requirements and, as a result, cause us to be in material breach of the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp;
See further discussions below regarding remedies for breach of the capacity purchase agreement by either Continental or
us.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Term and Termination of
Agreement and Remedies for Breach</i>.</b>&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement is scheduled to expire on December&nbsp;31,
2010.&nbsp; Continental has the option to extend the term of the agreement with 24&nbsp;months&rsquo; notice for up to four
additional five-year terms through December&nbsp;31, 2030.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental may terminate the
agreement early with 12 months&rsquo; notice, or for cause at any time without notice for cause.&nbsp; &ldquo;Cause&rdquo; is
defined as:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our bankruptcy;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">suspension or revocation of Airlines&rsquo; authority to operate as a scheduled airline;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">cessation of Airlines&rsquo; operations as a scheduled airline, other than as a result of a
union-authorized labor strike or any temporary cessation not to exceed 14&nbsp;days;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">a union-authorized labor strike that continues for 90 days; or</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">our intentional or willful material breach that substantially deprives Continental of the benefits
of the agreement, which is not cured within 90 days of notice of the breach.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental may also terminate
the agreement at any time upon our material breach that does not constitute cause, but continues uncured for 90&nbsp;days after we
receive notice of the breach.&nbsp; If we materially breach the agreement (including for cause) and, for breaches other than cause,
fail to cure the breach within 60&nbsp;days after we receive notice of the breach, we will have to pay Continental an amount equal
to the expected margin contained in the block hour rates for scheduled flights from the 60th day (or immediately, without receipt
of any notice, if the breach is for cause) until the breach is cured.&nbsp; In addition, Continental may terminate the agreement
immediately without notice or giving us an opportunity to cure if it makes a reasonable and good faith determination, using
recognized standards of safety, that there is a material safety concern with our operation of any flight under the capacity
purchase agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If Continental materially
breaches the agreement and fails to cure the breach within 60&nbsp;days after we notify it of the breach, we will be entitled to
obtain our payments directly from Airline Clearing House, Inc. from the 60th day for the duration of the default.&nbsp; In
addition, Continental and we are each entitled to seek damages in arbitration and to reach equitable remedies.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Disposition of Aircraft
upon Early Termination.</i></font></b>&nbsp; If Continental terminates the capacity purchase agreement for cause, it will also have
the right at that time to terminate Airlines&rsquo; leases or subleases for aircraft covered by the agreement and take possession
of these aircraft.&nbsp; If Continental terminates the capacity purchase agreement for any reason other than for cause, we have the
option to cancel all or any number of our leases or subleases with Continental for aircraft covered by the agreement at the time of
termination.&nbsp; However, if Airlines terminates any of these subleases, it will lose access to the subject aircraft, which would
reduce the size of our fleet and affect our future ability to generate revenue.&nbsp; If Airlines elects not to terminate these
leases or subleases, the capacity purchase agreement contains a provision for the interest rate implicit in calculating the
scheduled lease payments we make to Continental under the relevant leases or subleases to automatically increase by 200 basis
points.</p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Amendment of Embraer and
Rolls Royce Contracts.</i></font></b>&nbsp; We are prohibited, without Continental&rsquo;s consent, from amending Airlines&rsquo;
aircraft purchase agreements with Embraer to change the pricing, financing or leasing arrangements, number or delivery schedule of
firm order or option aircraft subject to the agreements, or to make any other changes that may be expected to adversely affect
Continental&rsquo;s rights under the capacity purchase agreement or our ability to perform our obligations under the capacity
purchase agreement.&nbsp; We have also agreed to consent to any amendment of Airlines&rsquo; Embraer aircraft purchase agreements
that reduces the financing or other obligations of Continental, provided that the amendment does not increase Airlines&rsquo;
obligations under these agreements.&nbsp; We are also prohibited, without Continental&rsquo;s consent, from amending our
power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce Corporation (&ldquo;Rolls Royce&rdquo;) in any manner that adversely affects
Continental&rsquo;s or our engine maintenance costs for the aircraft subject to the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; With
Continental&rsquo;s consent, we agreed to a five-year extension of our agreement with Rolls Royce and expanded the scope of its
coverage in 2003 and 2004, respectively<font color="black">.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<i>Indemnification</i></font></b>.&nbsp; In general, we have agreed to indemnify Continental and it has agreed to indemnify us for
any damages caused by any breaches of our respective obligations under the capacity purchase agreement or caused by our respective
actions or inactions under the agreement.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Board
Designee</i></b>.&nbsp; In October 2005, <font color="black">Continental relinquished its right under our capacity purchase
agreement to nominate a director to our board.</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Other Agreements with
Continental.</i></font></b>&nbsp; In connection with the capacity purchase agreement, we also entered into an administrative
services agreement, under which Continental provides us with services such as information technology support, transaction
processing, insurance and risk management and treasury administrative services, corporate real estate and environmental
affairs.&nbsp; Airlines also has a fuel purchasing agreement with Continental, under which Continental manages all of
Airlines&rsquo; fuel purchasing requirements.&nbsp; Continental charges us for these services and the cost is included in the block
hour rate pricing arrangement in the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, we have a tax
agreement with Continental that provides, among other things, for our payment to it of all or a significant portion of the tax
benefits we realize as a result of an internal reorganization performed before our initial public offering in 2002.&nbsp; Since our
initial public offering, we have made net payments of approximately $98.8 million to Continental under the tax agreement and could
pay Continental as much as an additional $257.4 million through 2017.&nbsp; See Item 8.&nbsp; "Financial Statements and
Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 9" for a detailed discussion of our income taxes
and our tax agreement with Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="acfleet"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Aircraft Fleet</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Our Fleet.</i></b>&nbsp; We
operate a fleet of 266 Embraer ERJ-135, ERJ-145 and ERJ-145XR aircraft as of December 31, 2005.&nbsp; We expect to take eight
additional aircraft in 2006 (three of which have been delivered as of February 27, 2006) for a total fleet count of 274
aircraft.&nbsp; We have no obligation to take any of the aircraft under firm commitments unless they are financed by a third party
and leased to Continental or us. &nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement
provides that through December 31, 2006 all of the 274 Embraer regional jets will be leased or subleased from Continental to
us.&nbsp; On December 28, 2005, Continental notified us that it intends to withdraw 69 aircraft, or 25% of the capacity currently
under the capacity purchase agreement, beginning December 28, 2006.&nbsp; The withdrawal schedule that Continental included in its
notice is as follows:</font></p>
