<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the terms of the capacity
purchase agreement, we have nine months (from the date of Continental&rsquo;s withdrawal notice) to decide if we will continue to
lease or sublease any or all of these aircraft or return them to Continental.&nbsp; Continental could withdraw additional aircraft
beginning December 28, 2009, with 12 months&rsquo; prior notice.&nbsp; In addition, Continental can terminate the agreement at
anytime with 12 months&rsquo; notice, under which withdrawal would be limited to 15 aircraft per month. If we return the aircraft
to Continental, it would incur costs associated with terminating the leases or subleases under the terms of the capacity purchase
agreement.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The operational capability of the
ERJ-135 and ERJ-145 is 1,100 nautical miles.&nbsp; The ERJ-145XR, with a 1,500 nautical mile range, continues to create
opportunities for us to expand Continental&rsquo;s network more economically to cities beyond its prior reach.&nbsp; Each of our
aircraft is equipped with advanced technology and certifications that aid our operation in challenging weather conditions, as well
as allowing for more cost-effective operations at higher flight levels.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our fleet offers a seamless
service experience to Continental&rsquo;s passengers.&nbsp; Our planes feature overhead baggage compartments, under-seat baggage
storage, leather seating, lavatories, in-flight meal and beverage service capabilities and jet-bridge loading in most
locations.&nbsp; Two differentiating features of our aircraft from mainline aircraft are the seating configuration (no middle
seats) and the opportunity for passengers to gate-check larger carry-on luggage and continue on to their connecting flight without
a trip to baggage claim.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have options for 100 ERJ-145XR
aircraft that may be exercised for other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; During 2005, Continental declined the
right to exercise any of these options.&nbsp; Continental is not required to participate in the financing for any option aircraft
that we acquire.&nbsp; We have no firm orders for additional aircraft other than the five remaining Embraer ERJ-145XR at February
27, 2006. We expect to notify Embraer of our intention regarding the first 25 option aircraft in March 2006.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Maintenance of
Aircraft.</i></b>&nbsp; We maintain our aircraft on both a scheduled and as needed basis using primarily our own trained and
FAA-certified personnel and facilities.&nbsp; We emphasize preventive maintenance in addition to inspection of our aircraft engines
and airframes at intervals required by the FAA.&nbsp; We perform line and heavy maintenance at our facilities in Burlington,
Vermont; Cleveland, Ohio; Houston, Texas; Knoxville, Tennessee; Richmond, Virginia; Louisville Kentucky; Shreveport, Louisiana and
Newark, New Jersey.&nbsp; We also perform line maintenance at our satellite maintenance stations.&nbsp; We maintain an inventory of
aircraft spare parts to ensure the reliability of our operations and utilize a computerized tracking system to increase maintenance
efficiency and avoid excess inventory of spare parts.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have a power-by-the-hour
agreement with Rolls Royce to maintain the engines on our aircraft through April 2015.&nbsp; Under the agreement, we are charged a
fixed rate based on flight hours incurred during a month.&nbsp; The rates are subject to annual revisions based on specific labor
and materials indices.&nbsp; We also have power-by-the-hour agreements with other vendors to cover various components and systems
on the aircraft, such as auxiliary power units, avionics, environmental controls, tires, wheels and brakes.&nbsp; For 2005,
approximately 70% of our maintenance, materials and repairs cost consisted of power-by-the-hour expenses.&nbsp; We believe that
these agreements, coupled with our ongoing maintenance program, reduce the likelihood of unexpected maintenance expense during the
aircraft lease terms.</font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, ExpressJet Services, our
repair and overhaul subsidiary, received a repair station certificate from the FAA enabling it to provide services to third
parties.&nbsp; ExpressJet Services currently offers a variety of composite and sheet metal repair and overhaul services, including
thrust reverser repairs, engine cowlings and engine nose section repairs, on many diverse aircraft types.&nbsp; We believe
ExpressJet Services allows us to pursue a strategy that leverages our expertise in aircraft reliability.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="industry"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Industry</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The airline industry in the
United States has traditionally been led by major airlines, including American Airlines, United Air Lines, Delta Air Lines,
Northwest Airlines, Continental and US Airways.&nbsp; These airlines operate primarily under the hub-and-spoke model, consisting of
large operations in a small number of metropolitan areas (hubs) providing extensive local non-stop service, as well as a connecting
point for traffic to or from other markets (spokes).</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The current strategies of the
major carriers include:&nbsp; lowering operating costs to match the revenue generating capability of their aircraft; broadening
their international networks to avoid domestic low-cost competition and to capture the higher fares paid on international routes;
continuing to focus on business travelers, who historically have paid higher fares; fighting to maintain capacity and market share
against low-cost carriers domestically; and bringing additional connecting traffic into their networks through new alliances.&nbsp;
Airlines have faced unprecedented challenges over the last five years, including the terrorist attacks in September 2001, severe
acute respiratory syndrome, the war in Iraq, underfunded defined benefit pension plans and record high fuel prices.&nbsp; Two
additional items added pressure to the major airlines:&nbsp; the Internet as a distribution system and low-cost carriers.&nbsp; The
Internet allows passengers to instantaneously compare all of the major network and low-cost airlines&rsquo; pricing, largely
eliminating lucrative travel agent and corporate contracts.&nbsp; In addition, the low-cost carriers continue to gain market share
at the expense of the majors by offering passengers no-frills travel at low fares.&nbsp; All of these factors have led four of the
six major airlines listed above to file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, and caused all of the six airlines to seek wage and
work rule concessions from their employees and concentrate on drastically reducing costs in their overall networks, including
bidding out regional flying to save money for the overall network.&nbsp; For the two major carriers, Continental and American
Airlines, that have not filed for Chapter 11 protection, there are further challenges as the bankrupt carriers run their operations
to generate cash under bankruptcy protection versus operating under a long-term viable business plan, which requires paying bills
regularly.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Regional airlines typically
operate under capacity purchase arrangements or prorate agreements with major airlines.&nbsp; The capacity purchase arrangement
allows a regional airline to sell all of its capacity to the major airline at a contracted price and concentrate on the operation
and efficiency of the aircraft versus marketing and scheduling the airline.&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement provides some
protection from industry conditions as well as a more predictable income stream.&nbsp; In this model, major carriers use the
regionals to serve smaller communities more economically than with larger jet aircraft to add departures at certain times of the
day in large markets to protect market share and to expand their network into new communities.&nbsp; Prorate agreements are less
common today and provide regional carriers a portion of the passenger revenue from the purchased ticket. &nbsp; Under a prorate
agreement, regional airlines are typically less insulated from industry conditions, such as low fares and high fuel prices.&nbsp;
However, prorate agreements allow regional airlines scheduling control of their aircraft, so the focus is to maximize profits
rather than bring connecting traffic into the major&rsquo;s hub.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Currently, we, as well as Air
Wisconsin, Mesa Airlines, Mesaba Airlines, Pinnacle Airlines, Republic Airways, SkyWest Airlines, including Atlantic Southeast
Airlines, and Trans States Airlines, operate under some form of capacity arrangement.&nbsp; Mesa Airlines also performs some
prorate flying.&nbsp; Other regional airlines, such as American Eagle, Comair and Horizon Airlines, are wholly owned subsidiaries
of major airline holding companies.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The principal challenge facing
the regional airline industry currently is the state of the overall airline industry and its effect on the major airlines.&nbsp;
Since all of the regional airlines depend upon agreements with the major airlines, the financial health of the major airlines is
fundamental to the regional airlines&rsquo; business model.&nbsp; With a majority of the major carriers in bankruptcy, regional
carriers have seen unprecedented challenges.&nbsp; For instance,</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Mesaba Airlines&rsquo; holding company filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection during 2005 after
Northwest awarded its flying to other partners;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">SkyWest Airlines purchased Atlantic Southeast Airlines from Delta Air Lines and paid aircraft
deposits to lengthen the term of their contract with Delta Air Lines after Delta Air Lines&rsquo; Chapter 11 filing; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Northwest Airlines bid out all of Pinnacle Airlines&rsquo; flying during 2005 (a replacement carrier
has not been named to date) and formed a subsidiary designed to fly 70 and 100-seat regional jets.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other items affecting regional
carriers include:&nbsp; increasing domestic air traffic making operating in high density environments more difficult, and size and
passenger perceptions of regional aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="compe"></a><a name="copetitors"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Competitors</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our main competitors include Mesa
Airlines, Mesaba Airlines, Pinnacle Airlines, Republic Airways and SkyWest Airlines, including Atlantic Southeast Airlines.&nbsp;
We also compete with other regional airlines, such as American Eagle, Comair and Horizon Airlines, which are wholly owned
subsidiaries of major airline holding companies.&nbsp; The three main areas of competition are:&nbsp; costs, customer service and
operational reliability.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Due to the variations among the
contracts under which regional airlines operate, cost comparisons between regional airlines are extremely difficult.&nbsp; We
believe that Airlines is one of the most cost-efficient providers of regional jet service due to the efficiencies it realizes by
operating a single fleet type and the economies of scale it achieves as one the world&rsquo;s largest regional airlines and the
launch customer for the Embraer ERJ-145 product line.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also believe that Airlines
provides one of the highest levels of customer service in the regional industry as evidenced by its top-tier performance in the
Department of Transportation (&lsquo;DOT&rdquo;) monthly surveys on customer complaints, mishandled bags and on-time
operations.&nbsp; In terms of reliability, Airlines accomplished a controllable completion factor, which excludes weather and air
traffic control cancellations, of 99.7% for the year ended December 31, 2005 versus our benchmark used for incentive payment
calculations of 99.3%.&nbsp; Our strong operational performance resulted in receipt of $4.2 million in incentive payments from
Continental in 2005.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="indregul"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Industry Regulation</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We operate under certificates of
public convenience and necessity issued by the DOT.&nbsp; These certificates may be altered, amended, modified or suspended by the
DOT if public convenience and necessity so require, or may be revoked for intentional failure to comply with the terms and
conditions of a certificate.&nbsp; We are regulated by the DOT, primarily in the areas of consumer protection, fitness and related
economic issues.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We also operate under an air
carrier operating certificate issued by the FAA which may be amended, modified, suspended or revoked if safety in air commerce or
air transportation and the public interest so require.&nbsp; The FAA regulates airlines, primarily in the areas of flight
operations, maintenance, ground facilities and other technical matters.&nbsp; Under these regulations, we have established, and the
FAA has approved, a maintenance program for the aircraft that Airlines operates, which provides for the ongoing maintenance of
these aircraft, ranging from frequent routine inspections to major overhauls.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Aviation and Transportation
Security Act of 2001 (&ldquo;ATSA&rdquo;) federalized substantially all aspects of civil aviation security and created the
Transportation Security Administration (&ldquo;TSA&rdquo;) under the Department of Homeland Security.&nbsp; Under the ATSA, all
security screeners at airports are either federal employees or contractors hired directly by the TSA, and other significant
elements of airline and airport security are overseen by federal employees, including federal security managers, federal law
enforcement officers, federal air marshals and federal security screeners.&nbsp; The law mandated improved flight deck security,
deployment of federal air marshals onboard flights, improved airport perimeter access security, airline crew security training,
enhanced security screening of passengers, baggage, cargo, mail, employees and vendors, enhanced training and qualifications of
security screening personnel, additional provision of passenger and cargo data to the U.S. Bureau of Customs and Border Protection
and enhanced airline employee background checks.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Funding for airline and airport
security under the law is provided by a $2.50 per enplanement ticket tax (up to $5.00 per one-way trip) and an additional Aviation
Security Infrastructure Fee (&ldquo;ASIF&rdquo;) on air carriers in an amount not to exceed the amounts paid in calendar year 2000
by air carriers for screening passengers and property.&nbsp; In February 2002, air carriers began collecting the new ticket tax
from passengers, and became subject to the new fee on air carriers.&nbsp; The Emergency Wartime Supplemental Appropriation Act of
2003 temporarily suspended the collection of the new ticket tax for ticket sales from June 1 to September 30, 2003 and the
additional ASIF on air carriers.&nbsp; Since September 2003, both the enplanement tax and air carrier portions have resumed.&nbsp;
On January 3, 2006, Airlines and 42 other carriers received demand notices from the TSA related to the alleged underreported,
uncollected ASIF.&nbsp; Airlines was invoiced by the TSA for an additional $2.1 million for 2005, due on or before February 2,
2006.&nbsp; We recorded this additional liability as of December 31, 2005, of which $0.8 million was recorded as additional
security expense pursuant to a previously agreed allocation methodology with Continental.&nbsp; On January 16, 2006, Continental
and we jointly submitted a letter to the TSA seeking a joint administrative review of the ASIF assessments and a stay of any
related payments.&nbsp; At this time, we cannot predict the outcome of such review.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The law also required the
Undersecretary of Transportation of Security to assume all the civil aviation security functions and responsibilities related to
passenger screening.&nbsp; Checked baggage must be screened by explosives detection systems, which has required significant
equipment acquisition by the government and the implementation of facility and baggage process changes.&nbsp; Further
implementation of the requirements of the ATSA and other security laws and regulations have resulted in increased costs for
airlines and passengers, delays and disruptions to air travel and reduced demand.&nbsp; The TSA has issued regulations implementing
the ATSA, including requirement for air carrier security programs and substantial civil penalties for violations. Under The Arming
Pilots Against Terrorism Act, the TSA has established a program to arm volunteer pilots of air carriers to protect aircraft.&nbsp;
The TSA is currently testing a new &ldquo;Secure Flight&rdquo; passenger screening program with the assistance of U.S.
airlines.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our operations are also subject
to increasingly stringent federal, state and local laws protecting the environment.&nbsp; In 2005, the TSA, FAA, Environmental
Protection Agency (&ldquo;EPA&rdquo;), Food and Drugs Administration all have proposed rulemaking that is pending and this trend is
expected to continue in 2006.&nbsp; These future regulatory developments could adversely affect operations and increase operating
costs in the airline industry.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="employees"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Employees</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of January 31, 2006, we had
approximately 6,700 employees, comprised of approximately 2,500 pilots and instructor pilots, 1,100 flight attendants, 1,100
customer service personnel, 1,100 mechanics and 100 other maintenance personnel, 80 dispatchers and 700 supervisors, management and
support personnel.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Labor costs are a significant
component of airline expenses and can substantially impact our results.&nbsp; While there can be no assurance that what we regard
as our generally good labor relations and high labor productivity will continue, a crucial component of our business strategy is
the preservation of good relations with our employees, approximately 70% of whom are represented by unions.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

January 31, 2006, reflects our principal collective bargaining agreements and their respective amendable dates:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; After amending our collective
bargaining agreements with our pilots, mechanics and dispatchers, we began negotiations with our flight attendants in November
2004.&nbsp; In September 2005, the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers (&ldquo;IAM&rdquo;), who
represents our flight attendants, and Airlines applied for federal mediation. Our negotiations were temporarily placed in recess by
the mediator, with no specified deadlines or dates for continued negotiations.&nbsp; We believe that a mutually acceptable
agreement can be reached with our flight attendants, although the ultimate outcome of these negotiations is unknown at this
time.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item1a"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1A.&nbsp; Risk Factors</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Factors that May Affect our Future Operating Results and Financial Condition</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our actual results of operations
and financial condition may vary materially from those anticipated, estimated or projected by us.&nbsp; Among the key factors that
could have an adverse effect on our future operating results and financial condition are those set forth below.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may not be able to design and execute satisfactory, income-generating arrangements for the
69 aircraft that Continental intends to withdraw from the capacity purchase agreement</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We received notice on December
28, 2005 from Continental of its intention to reduce by 69 the number of aircraft that we operate under the capacity purchase
agreement (a 25% reduction of capacity) beginning in December 2006.&nbsp; We have nine months from the date of notice to respond to
Continental and exercise our option to either retain or return the aircraft.&nbsp; We are currently evaluating whether to retain
the aircraft or return them to Continental.&nbsp; If we retain the aircraft, we cannot guarantee that we will be able to identify
or profitably execute any income-generating arrangements such as flying these aircraft under our own designator code or for other
parties or by subleasing them to third parties.&nbsp; Additionally, so long as Continental is our largest customer, if we enter
into a capacity purchase or similar arrangement with another carrier, that has annual revenues greater than $500 million (prior to
adjustment for inflation since 2000), for more than 10 aircraft at a less favorable net benefit to us than our capacity purchase
agreement with Continental, then the capacity purchase agreement has a provision that may allow Continental to amend its agreement
with us to be equally favorable.&nbsp; This most-favored-nations clause, as well as scope clauses in the collective bargaining
agreements of other major carriers, additional costs to put in place an infrastructure to support these aircraft independent of
Continental and other external factors (e.g., the U.S. economy, regulatory requirements, etc.) may limit our ability to
economically secure other arrangements for these aircraft.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We depend on the financial and operational stability of Continental</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are directly affected by the
financial and operation stability of Continental.&nbsp; Continental provides substantially all of our revenue through our capacity
purchase and other agreements.&nbsp; Despite improvements during the past year, the U.S. domestic airline environment continues to
be extremely challenging.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Since September 11, 2001,
Continental has reported significant losses, excluding special items.&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2005, Continental
reported a net loss of $68 million and has indicated that its business and financial results are affected by and are subject to a
number of factors, many of which are uncontrollable, such as low-cost competitors, the low-fare environment, higher fuel prices,
pension liability, terrorist attacks and adverse regulatory rulings.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We cannot predict the future
impact of these factors on Continental.&nbsp; Furthermore, high fuel prices, the long-term impact of the changes in fare structures
(most importantly in relation to business fares), booking patterns, low-cost competitor growth, customers&rsquo; direct booking on
the internet, competitor bankruptcies, and other changes in industry structure and conduct cannot be predicted at this time, but
could have a material adverse effect on both Continental&rsquo;s and our financial condition, liquidity and results of
operations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Our annual rate resetting process under the capacity purchase agreement with Continental may
result in arbitration</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase
agreement, we receive payment for each scheduled block hour in accordance with a formula designed to provide us with a target
operating margin of 10.0%.&nbsp; Since we have not agreed with Continental on rates for 2006, Continental has agreed to continue
paying Airlines at the December 2005 rates until an agreement is reached.&nbsp; Any agreement to revise the current rate structure
will be retroactive to January 1, 2006.&nbsp; We may not be successful in negotiating the rates for 2006 or may not be able to
retain our current target operating margin of 10.0%, considering the current challenges facing regional carriers, as described in
Item 1. &ldquo;Industry&rdquo; section above, and, ultimately, may have to submit our disagreement to arbitration.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Our capacity purchase agreement with Continental can still be terminated, even after the
recent fleet reduction notice</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beyond the 25% reduction notice,
Continental can terminate our capacity purchase agreement at any time with 12 months&rsquo; notice.&nbsp; If the agreement were
terminated, our revenue would be substantially eliminated after the pertinent wind-down period, as we receive substantially all of
our current revenues from our agreement with Continental and we would incur significant losses unless we were able to make other
arrangements.&nbsp; We cannot be certain that we would be able to enter into substitute arrangements, or if we could, that they
would be as favorable to us as our capacity purchase agreement with Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our capacity purchase agreement
is scheduled to terminate on December 31, 2010, subject to renewal by Continental through December 31, 2030.&nbsp; However,
Continental can terminate the agreement:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time for any reason with a minimum 12 months&rsquo; notice;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">for cause, as described in &ldquo;&mdash;Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements with
Continental,&rdquo; at any time without giving us notice or an opportunity to cure;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time upon our material breach that does not constitute cause, including our failure to
complete a specified percentage of our scheduled flights, if the breach continues for 90 days after we receive notice of the
breach; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">at any time, without giving us notice or an opportunity to cure, if Continental reasonably and in
good faith determines, using recognized standards of safety, that there is a material safety concern with our operation of any
flight under the capacity purchase agreement.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of the date of this report, we
have not received any notice from Continental other than the aircraft withdrawal notice described above.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>

</div>

</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may lose access to our aircraft, facilities and regulatory authorizations, as well as any
airport related services that Continental currently provides to us</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We sublease or lease all of our
aircraft from Continental.&nbsp; In addition, the regional jets subject to our remaining firm orders will be leased by Continental
and then subleased to us.&nbsp; If Continental terminates the capacity purchase agreement for cause, it will have the right to
terminate our leases and subleases for aircraft covered by the capacity purchase agreement at the time of termination.&nbsp;
Additionally, if Continental&rsquo;s financial condition deteriorated and it filed for bankruptcy protection, it would have the
ability to reject the leases or subleases on our aircraft.&nbsp; There can be no assurance that Continental will have sufficient
liquidity to fund its future operations and other financial obligations, especially in the event additional adverse factors beyond
its control occur, such as terrorist attacks, adverse regulatory rulings or higher fuel prices.<b></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, with the aircraft
reduction notice and the potential to terminate for any reason, we may lose access to some or substantially all of our airport
facilities and other services that Continental currently provides to us, as well as our take-off and landing slots and route
authorities.&nbsp; Continental leases most of the airport facilities that we use.&nbsp; We may be required to vacate the terminal
facilities (or all facilities if the termination results from our material breach of the capacity purchase agreement) that are
subleased to us by Continental, and to use commercially reasonable efforts to assign to Continental or its designee any lease in
our name.&nbsp; Consequently, to offer airline services, we would have to arrange to use the same or other airport facilities,
take-off or landing slots, route authorities and other regulatory authorizations used for scheduled flights at potentially higher
rates.&nbsp; We cannot provide any assurance that we would be able to gain appropriate access to airport facilities, slots or other
authorizations, or would not incur a significant increase in our costs to do so.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may not be able to successfully replicate the current passenger, traffic handling services,
administrative and other infrastructure services provided by Continental</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In connection with the capacity
purchase agreement and the administrative service agreement, Continental provides a number of important passenger, traffic
handling, corporate infrastructure, aviation insurance coverage, environmental compliance matters and administrative services to
us.&nbsp; Should we elect to insource or outsource these services to other third parties, we might not be able to replace these
services on a cost-effective basis, which could have a material adverse effect on our operating results and financial
condition.&nbsp; Additionally, under the current regulatory environment for public companies, the corporate infrastructure and
administrative system and process changes might result in control deficiencies in our internal control over financial reporting,
which could result in qualified audit opinions or disclaimers for internal control over financial reporting and for the financial
statements.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may not be successful in retaining qualified personnel to maintain the current level of
customer service and reliability and to design and execute our strategies in response to Continental&rsquo;s aircraft reduction
notice</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wage rates, in general, are
increasing.&nbsp; Therefore, our employees may elect to seek other employment opportunities, thereby increasing our recruiting and
training costs.&nbsp; We cannot guarantee that we will be able to find qualified personnel to fill our vacancies.&nbsp;
Additionally, our negotiations with our flight attendants, represented by the IAM, were temporarily placed in recess by the
mediator mutually requested by IAM and us, with no specified deadlines or dates for continued negotiations.&nbsp; We can provide no
assurance that a mutually acceptable agreement can be reached with our flight attendants.&nbsp; The ultimate outcome of these
negotiations is unknown at this time.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may not be successful in implementing any diversification strategy away from passenger
related airline services</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to our focus on
Continental&rsquo;s recent aircraft reduction notice, we continue to evaluate various diversification strategies away from
passenger-related airline services (such as aircraft maintenance, ground handling, crew training, etc.).&nbsp; Substantial risks
accompany these strategies, including:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may be responsible for additional taxes as a result of our tax agreement with
Continental</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have a tax agreement with
Continental that provides, among other things, for our payment to Continental of all or a significant portion of the tax benefits
we realize as a result of an internal reorganization effective prior to our initial public offering in 2002.&nbsp; Since that time,
we have made net payments of approximately $98.8 million to Continental under the tax agreement and could pay Continental as much
as an additional $257.4 million through 2017.&nbsp; See Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 9&rdquo; for a detailed discussion of our income taxes and such agreement with
Continental.&nbsp; If it were determined, as a result of an income tax audit or examination, that a significant amount of these tax
benefits should not have been available, thus requiring us to pay additional taxes, interest and penalties to one or more tax
authorities, and if at that time Continental were unable to indemnify us for these amounts, then we could be responsible for such
tax payments, interest and penalties.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may be unable to obtain all of the aircraft, parts or related support services we expect
from Embraer to operate the aircraft</font></i></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As we operate a single fleet type
produced by a single manufacturer, our operations could be materially adversely affected by:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="624">

</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Embraer&rsquo;s inability to fill our aircraft orders or provide sufficient parts or related support
services on a timely basis especially in light of its announcement to cease the production of our current fleet type;</font></p>
</td>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Our wage rates will likely increase as the number of aircraft under our capacity purchase
agreement decreases</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We may experience an increase in
wage rates if we are required to furlough employees due to the reduction in flying for Continental.&nbsp; Any furloughs would
necessarily affect more junior employees under our collective bargaining agreements first, resulting in the retention of more
senior employees at higher wage rates.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our board of directors has
implemented a long-term incentive plan to incentivize management employees as we seek to replace revenues from the capacity
withdrawn by Continental.&nbsp; If Continental terminated the capacity purchase agreement, it might be necessary to take additional
steps to ensure an orderly wind-down of that agreement.&nbsp; This likely increase in wages could cause our cost structure to be
less competitive when compared to other regional carriers.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Maintenance costs will likely increase as the average age of our fleet
increases</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Similar to other air carriers in
our industry, as the average age of our fleet increases, the maintenance costs of our fleet will likely increase.&nbsp; We
emphasize preventive maintenance, in addition to the inspection of our aircraft engines and airframes at intervals required by the
FAA.&nbsp; We perform line and heavy maintenance at our eight primary maintenance facilities and satellite stations located
throughout the Midwest and Eastern parts of the United States.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, we have a
power-by-the-hour agreement with Rolls Royce to maintain the engines on our aircraft through April 2015.&nbsp; Under the agreement,
we are charged a fixed rate based on flight hours incurred during a month.&nbsp; The rates are subject to annual revisions based on
specified labor and material indices.&nbsp; We also have power-by-the-hour agreements with other vendors to cover various
components and systems on aircraft, and will continue to evaluate and implement other such agreements, as long as the terms are
favorable.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We believe that these agreements,
coupled with our ongoing maintenance programs, reduce the likelihood of unexpected levels of maintenance expense during the terms
of our aircraft leases or subleases.&nbsp; Additionally, we continue to maintain an inventory of aircraft spare parts to ensure the
reliability of the operation and utilize a computerized tracking system to increase maintenance efficiency and to avoid excess
inventories of spare parts.&nbsp; However, our average maintenance costs could increase and adversely impact our results of
operations in the event that we have to address new FAA and/or Embraer maintenance directives or if Continental takes back the
newer aircraft in our fleet.&nbsp; We are not aware of any directives, changes, or out-of-the ordinary requirements from
Continental related to the return of the aircraft at this time that could adversely affect our maintenance costs.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We compete with both low-cost carriers and other regional carriers, and our cost structure may
not be competitive</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Because we do not control our own
flight schedule under the capacity purchase agreement, only 43% of our costs related to Airlines are controlled by us.&nbsp; All
other costs are driven by the flight schedule determined by Continental, Continental&rsquo;s own cost structure or factors that are
outside our control, or in some instances even Continental&rsquo;s control (such as aircraft rent, fuel, insurance, property taxes,
etc.).&nbsp; As a significant portion of our costs are allocated and/or inherited from Continental, we may not be able to
restructure our costs effectively to compete with other low-cost and regional carriers.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Our business is subject to extensive government regulation and we may incur additional costs
to comply with such regulations</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our business is subject to
extensive government regulation.&nbsp; As evidenced by the enactment of the ATSA, airlines are subject to extensive regulatory and
legal compliance requirements that result in significant costs.&nbsp; The FAA and other governmental agencies such as the EPA from
time to time issue directives and other regulations relating to the maintenance and operation of aircraft that require significant
expenditures.&nbsp; Some requirements cover, among other things, retirement of older aircraft, security measures, collision
avoidance systems, potable water standards, noise abatement and other environmental concerns, commuter aircraft safety and
increased inspections and maintenance procedures conducted on older aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We expect to continue incurring
expenses to comply with these regulations.&nbsp; In addition, if any of these regulations caused us to cancel flights, the
resulting reduction in our revenue would not be taken into account in any reconciliation payment made under the capacity purchase
agreement to maintain our operating margin within a specified range.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additional laws, regulations,
taxes and airport rates and charges are proposed from time to time that could significantly increase the cost of airline operations
or reduce revenue.&nbsp; Such laws, taxes and regulations have affected all facets of our operations from security at airports,
restrictions on landing, take-off, routes, restrictions on international routes, which can change spontaneously depending on the
current arrangements between the United States and the foreign governments, and increases in landing fees and other airport
facility charges.&nbsp; We cannot be certain that current laws or regulations, or laws or regulations enacted in the future, will
not adversely affect us.</font></p>

<div align="center"><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font></i>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">We may be adversely affected by factors beyond our control, including weather conditions and
the availability and cost of fuel</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Generally, revenue for airlines
depends on the number of passengers carried, the fare paid by each passenger and service factors, such as timeliness of departure
and arrival.&nbsp; During periods of fog, icy conditions, storms, hurricanes or other adverse weather conditions, flights may be
cancelled or significantly delayed.&nbsp; Under our capacity purchase agreement with Continental, we are substantially protected
against cancellations due to weather or air traffic control.&nbsp; However, if we decide in the future to operate our aircraft for
another airline or under our own flight designator code, we may not be protected against weather or air traffic control
cancellations, which could adversely affect our operating results and our financial condition.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, if we operate our
aircraft for another airline or under our own flight code, we could be exposed to the volatility of fuel prices.&nbsp; Both the
cost and availability of fuel are subject to various economic and political factors and events occurring throughout the
world.&nbsp; Significant changes or extended periods of high fuel cost or fuel supply disruptions would materially affect our
operating results.&nbsp; Our ability to pass on increased fuel costs through fare increases would be limited by several factors,
including economic and competitive conditions.&nbsp; Additionally, under the capacity purchase agreement, if the unavailability of
fuel causes us to cancel flights, our incentive revenue would be reduced.&nbsp; The cost and availability of adequate supplies of
fuel could have a material adverse effect on our operating results and our financial condition in the future.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Our operations and financial condition could be adversely affected as a result of an aviation
accident</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An accident or incident involving
one of our aircraft could involve repair or replacement of a damaged aircraft and its consequential temporary or permanent loss
from service, as well as significant potential claims of injured passengers and others.&nbsp; We are required by the DOT to carry
liability insurance.&nbsp; In the event of an accident, our liability insurance may not be adequate and we may be forced to bear
substantial losses from the accident.&nbsp; Substantial claims resulting from an accident in excess of our related insurance
coverage would harm operational and financial results.&nbsp; Moreover, any aircraft accident or incident, even if fully insured,
could create a public perception that we are less safe or reliable than other airlines.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item1b"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 1B.&nbsp; Unresolved Staff Comments</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We do not have any unresolved
staff comments as of the date of this filing.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

our operating fleet consisted of 266 regional jets at December 31, 2005.&nbsp; Our purchase commitments (firm orders) and aircraft
options as of December 31, 2005 are also shown below.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our options for the 100 ERJ-145XR
aircraft may be exercised for some other types of aircraft within the ERJ-145 Family.&nbsp; During 2005, Continental declined the
right to exercise any of these options.&nbsp; Continental is not required to participate in the financing for any option aircraft
that we acquire.&nbsp; We expect to notify Embraer of our intention regarding the first 25 option aircraft in March
2006.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2005, we put 21 new
ERJ-145XR aircraft into service.&nbsp; We expect to take delivery of eight ERJ-145XR aircraft in 2006 (three of which have been
delivered as of February 27, 2006).</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; See Item 7.&nbsp; "Management's
Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations - Liquidity and Capital Commitments" for a discussion of
our order for new firm commitment aircraft and related financing arrangements.</font></p>

31 regional jet gates.&nbsp; Subject to obtaining applicable approvals, we have the ability to add one additional regional jet gate
to the existing terminal. Additionally, we have remote parking positions for an additional 12 regional jets served by a bus
facility as well as access to an additional nine remote parking positions near the airport's international facility.</font></p>

Subject to obtaining applicable approvals, we have the ability to add 12 to 16 regional jet gates if the existing 24 turboprop
gates are eliminated.&nbsp; We currently have the ability to park up to 20 regional jets on the turboprop remote parking piers
adjacent to Terminal D.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Miami Maintenance Shop Facility &ndash; We own property consisting of approximately 2.5 acres of
land, including a maintenance shop with approximately 74,000 square feet located in Miami, Florida.&nbsp; We lease this property to
our partner American Composites, LLC for use in its aircraft repair and maintenance business.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Saltillo Aircraft Painting Facility &ndash; We own an aircraft painting facility that is currently
under construction, which, upon completion, will consist of approximately 96,000 square feet of hangar space and approximately
3,000 square feet of administrative space.&nbsp; The facility began construction in September 2005, and we expect it to be
completed in April 2006.&nbsp; We will lease this facility to our partner Saltillo Jet Center, S. de R.L. de C.V. for use in its
aircraft painting business.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All of these facilities are
leased on a net-rental basis, except for the Miami Maintenance Shop Facility and the Saltillo Aircraft Painting Facility, which are
owned by us.&nbsp; We are responsible for maintenance, taxes, insurance and other facility-related expenses and services at these
facilities.&nbsp; Continental is the primary sublessor for these facilities, except for the Houston maintenance hangar, the
Knoxville hangar and shop facilities, the Shreveport hangar and facility, the Corpus Christi and Lake Charles satellite maintenance
stations, which we lease directly.&nbsp; In addition, at each of Continental's three domestic hubs and many other locations, our
passenger and baggage handling space is provided by Continental on varying terms dependent on the prevailing practice at each
airport.&nbsp; If the capacity purchase agreement is terminated, we may be required to vacate the terminal facilities (or all
facilities if the termination results from our material breach of the agreement) that are subleased to us by Continental, and to
use commercially reasonable efforts to transfer to Continental or its designee any lease in our name.&nbsp; See Item 1. "Business -
Capacity Purchase and Other Agreements with Continental Airlines - Airport Facilities, Slots and Route Authorities."&nbsp; For a
period of five years following the termination of the capacity purchase agreement, if we wish to transfer our interests in any of
our facilities used to fulfill our obligations under the capacity purchase agreement, Continental must consent to the transfer
(where Continental is the sublessor) and has a right of first refusal to acquire our interests in those facilities that we lease
from parties other than Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item3"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 3.&nbsp; Legal Proceedings</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="lgproceedings"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Legal Proceedings</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are a defendant in various
lawsuits arising in the ordinary course of our business.&nbsp; While the outcome of these lawsuits and proceedings cannot be
predicted with certainty and could have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flows,
we believe that the ultimate disposition of these suits will not have a material adverse effect on our financial position, results
of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="environm"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Environmental Proceedings</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are and may from time to time
become involved in environmental matters, including the investigation and/or remediation of environmental conditions at properties
we use or were previously used by us.&nbsp; We are not, however, currently subject to any environmental cleanup orders imposed by
regulatory authorities, nor do we have any active investigations or remediation at this time.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have not paid any cash
dividends on our common stock and have no current plans to do so.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our certificate of incorporation
provides that no shares of capital stock may be voted by or at the direction of persons who are not United States citizens unless
they are registered on a separate stock record.&nbsp; Our bylaws further provide that no shares will be registered on this foreign
stock record if the amount to be registered would exceed United States foreign ownership restrictions.&nbsp; United States law
currently limits the voting power in us (or any other U.S. airline) by persons who are not citizens of the United States to
25%.</font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></b></p>

<p><a name="item6"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 6.&nbsp; Selected Financial Data</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This selected financial data
should be read together with the consolidated financial statements and related notes and Item 7.&nbsp; &ldquo;Management&rsquo;s
Discussions and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&rdquo; included elsewhere in this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Since January 1, 2001, Airlines
has operated under a capacity purchase agreement, pursuant to which Continental pays it an amount calculated using a formula for
each scheduled block hour that Airlines operates under the agreement.&nbsp; Under the formula, the rates vary depending on the
average length of the scheduled flights, the aggregate number of completed flights and the type of aircraft utilized and are
otherwise subject to specified adjustments.&nbsp; Substantially all of our revenue is received under the capacity purchase
agreement.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following selected financial
data, excluding operating statistics, have been derived from our audited financial statements.&nbsp; The financial information
included in this report is not necessarily indicative of our future results of operations, financial position and cash flows, or
reflective of what our results of operations, financial position and cash flows would have been had we been a stand-alone entity
during 2001.&nbsp; For a discussion of some of the key factors that could have an adverse effect on our results of operations,
financial position and cash flows, please refer to Item 1A. &ldquo;Risk Factors" beginning on page 18 of this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

passenger airline services.&nbsp; Exclusion of expenses not related to passenger airline services in the calculation of various
operating statistics provides more accurate information related to the performance of our flight operations.&nbsp; All operating
costs prior to 2005 were related to flight operations.</font></p>
