<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="item7"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Item 7.&nbsp; Management's Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and
Results of Operations</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The information contained in this
section has been derived from our historical financial statements and should be read together with our historical financial
statements and related notes included elsewhere in this report.&nbsp; The discussion below contains forward-looking statements that
involve risks and uncertainties.&nbsp; Our actual results may differ materially from those expressed or implied in these
forward-looking statements as a result of various factors, including those described in Item 1A.&nbsp; &ldquo;Risk Factors&rdquo;
and elsewhere in this report.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="execsummary"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Executive Summary</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Review of
2005</i></b></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have strategic investments in
the air transportation sector.&nbsp; Our principal asset is all of the issued and outstanding shares of stock of XJT Holdings,
Inc., the sole stockholder of Airlines, which operates as Continental Express.&nbsp; Airlines is one of the largest regional
airlines in the world, based on available seat miles and number of regional jets, transporting passengers, cargo and
mail.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Airlines currently flies
exclusively on behalf of Continental pursuant to our capacity purchase agreement and substantially all of our revenue is received
under that agreement.&nbsp; Airlines provides all of Continental's regional jet service out of New York/Newark, Houston and
Cleveland, as well as non-hub service.&nbsp; We believe Airlines&rsquo; operations complement Continental's network.&nbsp; The
capacity purchase agreement currently covers all of our existing fleet and the remaining regional jets subject to our firm aircraft
orders; however, Continental announced on December 28, 2005 its plan to remove 69 aircraft from the agreement beginning in December
2006 and ending in June 2007.&nbsp; Although we began diversifying our operations in 2005, we remain economically dependent on
Continental.&nbsp; The capacity purchase agreement gives us up to nine months from Continental&rsquo;s notice date to decide if we
want to retain the aircraft.&nbsp; If we choose to retain the aircraft, the capacity purchase agreement contains a provision for
the interest rate implicit in calculating the scheduled lease payments that we make to Continental to increase by 200 basis
points.&nbsp; We are currently exploring opportunities for the 69 aircraft.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of January 31, 2006, we
offered scheduled passenger service averaging 1,233 daily departures to 152 cities in 40 states and the District of Columbia,
Guatemala, Mexico, Canada and the Caribbean.&nbsp; Our available seat miles have grown at a compounded annual rate of 20.4% from
4.7 billion in 2000 to 12.0 billion in 2005.&nbsp; We generated $1.6 billion of revenue and $98.0 million of net income for the
year ended December 31, 2005.&nbsp; Please refer to our consolidated financial statements included in this report for information
regarding our revenue and net income for each of the last three fiscal years and our total assets at the end of the last two fiscal
years.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Fleet</i></b><i>.&nbsp;</i>
During 2005, we accepted 21 new ERJ-145XR aircraft.&nbsp; This aircraft is a 50-seat regional jet capable of flights of 1,500
miles.&nbsp; With these deliveries, we ended 2005 with 96 ERJ-145XR, 140 ERJ-145 and 30 ERJ-135 aircraft.&nbsp; Our regional jets'
operational capabilities allowed us to add service to new markets, expand service in existing markets and ultimately allowed
Continental to broaden service from its hub cities as well as select communities, thus contributing to Continental's growth
options.&nbsp; We currently expect to receive eight new ERJ-145XR aircraft during 2006 (three of which have been delivered as of
February 27, 2006).</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Labor.</b>&nbsp;</font></i>
As of January 31, 2006, approximately 70% of our employees were covered by collective bargaining agreements.&nbsp; We amended our
contracts with our pilots, dispatchers and mechanics in 2004.&nbsp; The new contracts will be amendable in December 2008, July 2009
and August 2009, respectively.&nbsp;</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our contract with our flight
attendants, approximately 16% of our employees, became amendable in December 2004.&nbsp; In September 2005, the IAM, which
represents our flight attendants, applied for federal mediation.&nbsp; Our negotiations were temporarily placed in recess by the
mediator, with no specified deadlines or dates for continued negotiations.&nbsp; We believe that a mutually acceptable agreement
can be reached with our flight attendants, although the ultimate outcome of these negotiations is unknown at this time.&nbsp; As
contracts become amendable, we accrue for any expected increase in costs related to the new contracts.&nbsp; The actual outcome may
differ from our estimates.</font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Relationship with
Continental.</b></font></i>&nbsp; Continental currently owns less than 10% of our common stock.&nbsp; In October 2005, Continental
relinquished its right to nominate a director to our board.&nbsp; Continental has indicated that it intends to dispose of some or
all of its remaining interest in our common stock, subject to market conditions.&nbsp; Based on current information and our
capacity purchase agreement with Continental, we do not believe that Continental&rsquo;s disposition of its remaining ownership
interest in us will have an adverse impact on our results of operations or financial position.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>2006 Rate Setting Process
under the Capacity Purchase Agreement.</i></b>&nbsp; We negotiate with Continental to adjust the scheduled block hour rates
annually as required under the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Because we have not agreed on the 2006 rates, Continental has
agreed to continue paying us at the December 2005 rates until an agreement is reached.&nbsp; Any agreement to revise the current
rate structure will be retroactive to January 1, 2006.&nbsp; We cannot currently estimate what our 2006 rates will ultimately
be.&nbsp; If we cannot agree on the 2006 rates, the capacity purchase agreement allows either party to submit the matter to
arbitration.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We seek to provide the most
reliable regional jet services available at a competitive price and continuously try to identify ways to lower our costs.&nbsp; As
this occurs, our results from operations could be adversely affected in the short-run when compared to historical results since
substantially all of our operating revenue is based on our underlying costs.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Business
Ventures.</i></b><i>&nbsp;</i> Our consistent earnings and improving balance sheet have helped position us for new
opportunities.&nbsp; We continue to seek strategic opportunities that leverage our internal strengths, such as our technical,
training and fleet and asset management capabilities, to develop and implement additional business strategies.&nbsp; We made the
following non-controlling cash investments in 2005 (see Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to
Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 1 &ndash; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies &ndash; (i)&rdquo; for the
accounting treatment of each of the investments):</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">In March 2005, we purchased 50% minus one share of JetX Aviation Limited, dba ExpressJet Europe
(&ldquo;JetX Aviation&rdquo;) for $0.9 million.&nbsp; JetX Aviation is a European start-up company that seeks to provide regional
jet service to European air carriers.&nbsp; The start-up company is currently attempting to market this concept, but is not yet a
certificated airline and does not yet have a commitment from an air carrier.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">In June 2005, we purchased 49% of Wing Holdings, LLC (&ldquo;Wing Holdings&rdquo;) for $16.0
million.&nbsp; Wing Holdings is a full-service aviation company specializing in high-quality aircraft charter and management,
airframe maintenance, avionics installations and aircraft painting.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">In July 2005, we purchased 49% of American Composites, LLC (&ldquo;American Composites&rdquo;) and
purchased certain building, land and related improvements (from a party related to American Composites) for an aggregate price of
approximately $5.8 million.&nbsp; $4.9 million of the purchase price was recorded as building, land and related improvements and
the balance was recorded as our non-controlling investment in the company.&nbsp; American Composites provides maintenance, repair
and overhaul services of aircraft composite and sheet metal parts and structures to Airlines and other parties.&nbsp; At the same
time, we lease the building, land and related improvements to American Composites for use in its operation.&nbsp; We account for
the lease as an operating lease.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, we purchased InTech
Aerospace Services, LP (&ldquo;InTech&rdquo;), an aircraft interior refurbishment company for $3.0 million in November 2005.&nbsp;
We believe this entity will complement our current aircraft maintenance infrastructure and allow us to diversify our passenger
related airline services.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2005, we also began
construction of an aircraft painting facility in Mexico.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, the cost of this facility was $5.0
million.&nbsp; The total cost of the facility is expected to be $8.7 million, and we expect to complete it during the second
quarter of 2006.&nbsp; We believe the services to be provided by this facility will enhance the product offerings of our current
subsidiaries and investments.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In January 2006, we purchased a
non-controlling interest in Flight Services &amp; Systems, Inc. (&ldquo;FSS&rdquo;) for $4.0 million.&nbsp; <font color="black">FSS
is based in Cleveland, Ohio and provides airport services to support airlines, airports and the FAA.</font></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2005, we also announced
that our wholly-owned subsidiary, ExpressJet Services, and ExpressJet Airlines&rsquo; Training Services division received
third-party repair and training certificates, respectively, from the FAA.&nbsp; We anticipate that these certifications will allow
us to generate additional income as we provide outsourced services to other airlines or aviation-related entities.&nbsp; In the
fourth quarter of 2005, ExpressJet Services entered into an agreement with Aircelle Safran Group to become its premier North
American repair facility for thrust reversers and nacelles on aircraft within the ERJ-145 Family, the Embraer 170 and the Legacy
aircraft.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Securities Repurchase
Program.</i></b>&nbsp; In July 2005, our board of directors authorized the expenditure of up to $30 million to repurchase shares of
our common stock.&nbsp; Subsequently in February 2006, the board authorized the inclusion of our 4.25% senior convertible notes due
2023 in this program.&nbsp; Stock purchases have been made from time to time in the open market.&nbsp; The timing of any notes or
stock repurchases under the program depends on a variety of factors, including market conditions, and may be suspended or
discontinued at any time.&nbsp; Common stock acquired through the program will be available for general corporate purposes and
convertible notes acquired under the program will be cancelled.&nbsp; Since the inception of the plan, we have purchased 590,800
shares of our common stock at an average cost per share of $9.55.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Liquidity and Financing
Activities.</i></b> &nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, we had $236.5 million in cash and short term investments, including $9.2
million in restricted cash.&nbsp; During 2005, we reduced our note payable to Continental by $81.3 million and our loan agreement
with Export Development Canada (&ldquo;EDC&rdquo;) by $0.9 million.&nbsp; In addition, we made $0.8 million in principal payments
related to our capital leases.&nbsp; Additionally, we negotiated the sale of eight engines to Rolls Royce and, in exchange, entered
into seven new engine leases with a Rolls Royce subsidiary in December 2005.&nbsp; Net proceeds received for this transaction were
$15.3 million, which we reported as cash flow from financing activities.&nbsp; Our cash flows from operations were sufficient to
cover our capital resources and liquidity requirements during the three years ending December 31, 2005.&nbsp; See discussion below
in &ldquo;&ndash; Liquidity and Capital Commitments.&rdquo;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Outlook for
2006</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We will continue seeking to
enhance our stockholders&rsquo; value by providing the most cost-efficient and reliable regional jet service for our customer,
including achieving the highest level of customer satisfaction in the regional industry.&nbsp; In the long-run, we believe this
strategy serves us well, although we continue to be affected by the pressures affecting the airline industry generally.&nbsp; As
discussed above, on December 28, 2005, Continental announced that it would seek an alternate regional service provider for 69 of
the aircraft currently covered by our capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Moreover, we have not yet been able to reach an agreement
with Continental relating to the rates applicable for 2006 under the capacity purchase agreement. See &ldquo;2006 Rate Setting
Process under the Capacity Purchase Agreement&rdquo; above.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; During 2006, we will continue
exploring ways to enhance stockholders' long-term value through:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>Our Dependence on
Continental</b></font></i></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite our efforts to contain
costs and improve reliability, we are directly affected by the financial and operational stability of Continental because we depend
on Continental&rsquo;s ability to make payments to us under our capacity purchase and other agreements, which continue to be the
predominant source of our revenue.&nbsp; Continental has had substantial losses since September 11, 2001 and has indicated that
losses of this magnitude are not sustainable.&nbsp; In addition, Continental has announced that its current cost structure is not
competitive within the weak domestic yield environment, caused in large part by the fierce competition from low-cost carriers and
record high fuel prices.&nbsp; Furthermore, Continental may face stronger competition from major carriers that have filed for
bankruptcy protection, allowing them to achieve substantial cost reductions, including reducing or discharging debt, lease and
pension obligations.&nbsp; The current U.S. domestic network carrier financial environment continues to be poor and could
deteriorate further as a result of these factors.&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Continental and the union
representing its flight attendants recently ratified their labor agreement to allow Continental to meet its $0.5 billion
cost-savings goal previously announced; absent additional adverse factors due to external influences, such as additional terrorist
attacks or unreasonable increase in fuel prices, we are not aware of any other factors that would lead us to believe that
Continental will not be able to maintain adequate liquidity through December 31, 2006, as previously disclosed in its quarterly
filings.&nbsp; However, it has significant financial obligations due in 2007 and thereafter, and it is possible that Continental
will have inadequate liquidity to meet those obligations if the current adverse economic environment for network carriers does not
improve materially.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, Continental leases
from third parties a substantial portion of the aircraft and airport facilities that it subleases to us.&nbsp; If Continental
breaches or otherwise fails to perform under these leases, we could lose our rights under the subleases, and our continued access
to our aircraft and airport facilities would then depend on our ability to negotiate direct agreements with the third-party
lessors.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Critical Accounting
Policies and Estimates</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our consolidated financial
statements have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&ldquo;GAAP&rdquo;).&nbsp; The
preparation of these financial statements requires us to make estimates and judgments that affect reported amounts and related
disclosures.&nbsp; We have identified the accounting policies and estimates below as critical to our business operations and
understanding of our results of operations.&nbsp; The SEC has defined critical accounting policies and estimates as the ones that
are most important to the portrayal of a company&rsquo;s financial condition and results and require the company to make its most
difficult and subjective judgments, often as a result of the need to make estimates of matters that are inherently uncertain.&nbsp;
For all of these estimates, we caution that future events rarely develop exactly as forecasted, and the best estimates routinely
require judgment.&nbsp; The discussion below is not intended to be a comprehensive list of our accounting estimates and
policies.&nbsp; For a detailed discussion on the application of our accounting policies, see Item 8.&nbsp; &ldquo;Financial
Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash; Note 1.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="682">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Revenue Recognition</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Nature of Estimates Required &ndash;</font></i> Certain amounts billed by us to Continental under
the capacity purchase agreement are subject to our interpretation of the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; Continental may dispute
the amount billed and pay less than the amount invoiced if it interprets the capacity purchase agreement differently than we
do.&nbsp; Additionally, under the capacity purchase agreement, beginning in 2005, new rates are to be determined
annually.&nbsp;</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Assumptions and Approach Used &ndash;</font></i> Our operating revenue is calculated based on our interpretation of the capacity
purchase agreement.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Effect if Different Assumptions Used</font></i> &ndash; If our interpretation differs materially from Continental&rsquo;s, our
revenue could be materially understated or overstated.&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase agreement, a substantial portion of
Airlines&rsquo; costs are reconciled for differences between Airlines&rsquo; actual costs and estimated costs included in its block
hour rates at a 10.0% operating margin.&nbsp; Under Airlines&rsquo; 2005 rates, certain costs generally controllable by Airlines
are reconciled to allow it to operate within its operating margin, as defined in the capacity purchase agreement (&ldquo;prevailing
margin&rdquo;) of 8.5% to 10.0%.&nbsp; For the fourth quarter of 2005, we rebated $4.2 million to Continental because
Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin before reconciliation payments exceeded 10.0%.&nbsp; If Continental had successfully challenged
any of our billings in the fourth quarter 2005, for example, resulting in a one percentage point increase in the prevailing margin
before any reconciliation payment, our pretax income would have decreased by $4.5 million, or $0.05 per diluted earnings per common
share (&ldquo;Diluted EPS&rdquo;).</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Wages, Salaries and Related Expenses</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Nature of Estimates Required &ndash;</font></i> We are currently self-insured for a portion of
our healthcare costs and have a large deductible for our workers compensation liability.&nbsp; Consequently, reserves for the cost
of claims that have not been paid or benefit costs that have been incurred but not yet reported (&ldquo;IBNR&rdquo;) as of a given
date are estimated.&nbsp; In addition, as our collective bargaining agreements become amendable, we accrue for anticipated
retroactive pay that we estimate will be due under the new contract.&nbsp; However, actual costs may differ materially from our
estimates.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Assumptions and Approach Used &ndash;</font></i> Our estimates for these reserves are based on recommendations from actuarial
projections provided by third-party actuaries.&nbsp; These estimates rely on historical claim experience, demographic data and
projection of the effects of inflation on medical costs.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Effect if Different Assumptions Used</font></i> &ndash; If the ultimate development of these claims is significantly different
than our estimates, the accrual for future healthcare claims could be materially overstated or understated.&nbsp; As of December
31, 2005, our reserve related to our healthcare cost was $3.0 million.&nbsp; Our third-party actuary provided an estimated IBNR
range of $2.3 million to $3.4 million.&nbsp; Had we changed our reserve to either the low end or the high end of the reserve, the
impact to our net income would have been immaterial as a result of the mechanics of the capacity purchase agreement with
Continental. Our workers&rsquo; compensation actuary provided a range of IBNR from $6.6 million to $7.7 million in 2005.&nbsp; As
of December 31, 2005, we reserved $7.7 million related to these benefits.&nbsp; Had our reserve equaled the low end of the
estimate, the impact to our net income would have been immaterial due to the 2005 rate amendment under the capacity purchase
agreement.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<td valign="top">

relating to flight equipment are carried at average acquisition cost and are expensed when used.&nbsp; Inventories are carried at
the lower of amortized cost or net realizable value.&nbsp; The adequacy of our allowance for obsolescence requires a high degree of
judgment.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Assumptions and Approach Used&ndash;</font></i> Our allowance for obsolescence related to inventory is provided over the remaining
useful life of the related aircraft, plus allowance for spare parts currently identified as excess.&nbsp; Part of the calculation
for this reserve is based on historical experience.&nbsp; In addition, we may reserve for additional obsolescence when current
available market data indicate a decline in the fair value of parts or if we deem parts as excess inventory.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Effect if Different Assumptions Used</font></i>&ndash; As of December 31, 2005, our allowance for obsolescence related to our
spare parts and supplies was approximately $9.1 million.&nbsp; If we increase the reserve by 10%, due to the mechanics of the
capacity purchase agreement, the impact on pre-tax income is immaterial.</p>

other municipal authorities.&nbsp; In order to determine the proper classification of a lease as either an operating lease or a
capital lease, we must make certain estimates at the inception of the lease relating to the economic useful life and the fair value
of an asset, as well as select an appropriate discount rate to be used in discounting future lease payments.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="682">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Effect if Different Assumptions Used</font></i>&ndash; As all our aircraft and facility leases have been classified as operating
leases, rental payments are charged to expense over the terms of the related leases.&nbsp; Moreover, since operating leases are not
reflected on our balance sheet, if different assumptions were used, which might cause an operating lease to be classified as a
capital lease, the impact to our financial statements would be a gross-up of our property and equipment and capital lease
obligations and a charge to depreciation and amortization expense.&nbsp;</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Goodwill and Intangible Assets</font></b></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">Nature of Estimates Required&ndash;</font></i> Under Statement of Financial Accounting Standard
No. 142&ndash;&ldquo;Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets&rdquo; (&ldquo;SFAS 142&rdquo;), intangible assets can have either finite
or indefinite useful lives.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, we had intangible assets with both definite and indefinite lives.&nbsp;
Our critical accounting estimate is related to our &ldquo;Reorganization Value in Excess of Amounts Allocable to Identifiable
Assets,&rdquo; which has indefinite useful life.&nbsp; Under SFAS 142, goodwill and intangible assets with indefinite useful lives
should be tested at least annually for impairment.&nbsp; Factors considered important when determining the impairment of reporting
segments under SFAS 142 include items affecting the cash flows of the reporting segments; the reporting segments&rsquo; operational
performance versus market expectations; the reporting segments&rsquo; performance compared to peers within the industry; the
marketplace for and identification of the intangible asset of the reporting segments; significant changes in the underlying
business strategy or operational environment; material ongoing industry or economic trends; or other factors specific to the asset
or reporting segments being evaluated.&nbsp; Any changes in the key assumptions about the business and its prospects, or changes in
market conditions or other externalities could result in an impairment charge.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Assumptions and Approach Used &ndash;</font></i> For our SFAS 142 analysis, we employed a discounted cash flow approach, a market
multiple approach and an acquisition approach.&nbsp; The discounted cash flow approach considers our expected cash generation
capabilities, and the market&ndash;multiple approach and the acquisition approach analyzes similar companies or transactions within
the industry to derive multiples for the company. <i>&nbsp;</i></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"><br />
 Effect if Different Assumptions Used</font></i>&ndash; As of December 31, 2005, our &ldquo;Reorganization Value in Excess of
Amounts Allocable to Identifiable Assets&rdquo; was $12.8 million.&nbsp; In addition to our annual SFAS 142 analysis at June 30,
due to Continental&rsquo;s announcement on December 28, 2005 of its intention to withdraw 69 aircraft from the capacity purchase
agreement beginning in December 2006, we determined a trigger event occurred.&nbsp; In accordance with our policy, we performed a
SFAS 142 impairment analysis as soon as reasonably possible after the trigger event, using the latest data available.&nbsp; No
impairment was identified.&nbsp; If assumptions used in our analysis were changed materially, our intangible assets could be
materially overstated.&nbsp; However, based on our most current impairment test, there would have to be a significant change in
assumptions used in the calculation for an impairment to occur as of December 31, 2005.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to our critical
accounting estimates and policies described above, we made other estimates that, while not involving the same degree of judgment,
are important to understanding our financial statements.&nbsp; In general, we base our estimates on historical experience,
information from third-party professionals and various other assumptions that we believe are reasonable under the
circumstances.&nbsp; We continually evaluate our accounting policies and the estimates used to prepare our consolidated financial
statements.&nbsp; Our estimates as of the date of the financial statements reflect our best judgment after giving consideration to
all currently available facts and circumstances.&nbsp; As such, actual results may differ significantly from these estimates and
may require adjustment in the future as additional facts become known or as circumstances change.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We have discussed the development
and selection of these critical accounting policies and estimates with the Audit Committee of our board of directors, and the
Committee has reviewed the disclosures presented above.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recently Issued Accounting
Standards</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Financial Accounting
Standards Board (&ldquo;FASB&rdquo;) issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No. 123 (Revised 2004) &mdash;
&ldquo;Share-Based Payments&rdquo; (&ldquo;SFAS 123R&rdquo;) which impacted our method of accounting for our stock
compensation.&nbsp; See detailed description of this accounting standard and its impact on our financial condition, results of
operations and liquidity in Item 8. &ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash; Notes to Consolidated Financial
Statements &ndash; Note 1 &ndash; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies.&rdquo;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;</font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(1)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Revenue passenger miles are the number of scheduled miles flown by revenue passengers.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(2)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Available seat miles are the number of passenger seats available multiplied by the number of
scheduled miles those seats are flown.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(3)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Passenger load factor equals revenue passenger miles divided by available seat miles.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(4)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating costs related to our flight operations are costs incurred by Airlines.&nbsp; For 2005,
operating costs related to our flight operations were $1.4 billion, which excluded $2.8 million of operating costs not related to
passenger airline services.&nbsp; Exclusion of expenses not related to passenger airline services in the calculation of various
operating statistics provides more accurate information related to the performance of our flight operations.&nbsp; All operating
costs prior to 2005 were related to flight operations.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(5)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per available seat mile is operating costs related to our flight operations divided
by available seat miles.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(6)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Block hours are the hours from gate departure to gate arrival.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(7)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Operating cost per block hour is operating costs related to our flight operations divided by block
hours.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<div align="center"><font size="3" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(8)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Fuel cost used in calculations includes cost of fuel and related fuel tax.&nbsp; Airlines incur fuel
expense and fuel tax equal to the lower of the actual cost or the agreed-upon caps of 66.0 cents and 5.2 cents per gallon,
respectively, based on our fuel purchase agreement with Continental.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(9)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Average daily utilization of each aircraft is the average number of block hours per day that an
aircraft in revenue service is operated.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">(10)&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">Controllable completion factor is the actual number of completed flights, plus flights cancelled due
to weather and air traffic control, divided by the number of scheduled flights.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We monitor the forgoing
statistical information closely to ensure that we are continually focused on our operational efficiencies and cost
control.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The following discussion provides
an analysis of our results of operations and reasons for any material changes for the periods indicated.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Comparison of 2005 to
2004</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Operating
Revenue</i></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our operating income in 2005
reflected a 10.0% operating margin, compared with an operating margin of 13.6% in 2004.&nbsp; As part of the 2005 rate negotiation,
Airlines agreed to cap its prevailing margin at 10.0% in lieu of the margin cap of 11.5% in 2004.&nbsp;&nbsp; Beginning in 2005,
Airlines also includes previously unreconciled costs within the margin band, such as wages, salaries and related costs, although it
is not reimbursed if these costs are higher than agreed in the block hour rates and cause its prevailing margin to fall below the
8.5% margin floor.&nbsp; The 2004 operating margin included the benefits of cost savings in Airlines&rsquo; previously unreconciled
costs and $11.5 million in performance incentive payments under Airlines&rsquo; capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; The 2005
operating margin included $4.2 million of performance incentive payments.&nbsp; Cost savings related to previously unreconciled
costs were included in the prevailing margin calculation, hence they did not impact the 2005 operating margin.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The incentive payments are
primarily based on the current controllable completion factor compared to a historical controllable completion factor
benchmark.&nbsp; Because the historical rates are measured on a rolling monthly average, higher controllable completion factors
result in higher incentive payments in the near term but reduce Airlines&rsquo; opportunity to earn incentive payments in the
future.&nbsp; Airlines&rsquo; controllable completion factor in 2005 was 99.7% and its historical benchmark completion factor was
99.3% for the same period.&nbsp; As part of the 2005 rate resetting, Airlines is only required to pay Continental a penalty for
controllable completion factors below 99.5% instead of using its rapidly rising historical benchmark.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a substantial portion of
Airlines&rsquo; costs under the capacity purchase agreement are reconciled for differences between its actual costs and the
estimated costs included in its block hour rates at a 10.0% operating margin, if Airlines&rsquo; prevailing margin (before any
reconciliation payments) fell outside its margin band of 8.5% to 10.0% for 2005 and 8.5% to 11.5% for 2004, Airlines&rsquo; revenue
would have been adjusted to bring it back to its floor or cap.&nbsp; In 2005 and 2004, Airlines&rsquo; actual cost efficiencies
brought its prevailing margin above 10.0% and 11.5%, respectively.&nbsp; Reconciliation payments to Continental totaled $23.4
million and $61.0 million for 2005 and 2004, respectively.&nbsp; The 2005 reconciliation payment was primarily driven by lower
actual wages, salaries and related costs and maintenance, materials and repair expenses as compared to the estimated costs in the
block hour rates.&nbsp; The 2004 reconciliation payment was primarily driven by lower actual maintenance, materials and repair and
passenger servicing expenses as compared to the estimated costs in the block hour rates.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We negotiate with Continental to
adjust the scheduled block hour rates annually as required under the capacity purchase agreement.&nbsp; As of February 28, 2006, we
are still negotiating the rates for 2006.&nbsp; Continental has agreed to continue paying us at the December 2005 rates during
these negotiations.&nbsp; Any agreement to revise the current rate structure will be retroactive to January 1, 2006.&nbsp; We
cannot currently estimate what our 2006 rates will ultimately be.&nbsp; If we cannot agree on the 2006 rates, the capacity purchase
agreement allows either party to submit the matter to arbitration.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We do not expect
Continental&rsquo;s withdrawal of the 69 aircraft from the capacity purchase agreement beginning in December 2006 to have a
material adverse impact on our results of operations in 2006.&nbsp; Beyond 2006, we cannot estimate the impact the withdrawal of
these aircraft from the capacity purchase agreement will have on our results of operations or financial condition as the impact
will be determined based on many factors unknown to us at this time such as our decision to retain these aircraft or return them to
Continental and our ability to implement and execute income-generating arrangements for these aircraft.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Operating
Expenses</i></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Although our operations, measured
by block hours, grew over 13.4% for the year ended December 31, 2005, wages, salaries and related costs only increased by
9.5%.&nbsp; This resulted from our continuous focus on managing our non-union labor costs and improving productivity related to our
unionized labor force to remain competitive with our peers.&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2005, wages increased by $21.7
million.&nbsp; In addition, we incurred approximately $6.7 million higher employee benefit costs, such as medical coverage,
workers&rsquo; compensation costs, profit sharing and 401(k) expenses in 2005.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the future, we anticipate that
our wages, salaries and related costs may be affected by the following factors:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">potential wage increases to incentivize key personnel to remain with us as we design and execute our
diversification strategies in response to Continental&rsquo;s recent notice of aircraft withdrawal, including our long-term
incentive plan implemented in January 2006;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">wage rate increases in accordance with our collective bargaining agreements as a result of higher
seniority of our work force;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">projected increases in health and medical benefit costs; and</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">expected expenses related to the fair value of stock compensation beginning in January 2006, as
required by SFAS 123R.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The increase in our aircraft fuel
expense in 2005 was mainly due to a 12.4% increase in fuel consumption.&nbsp; Consumption rose primarily due to a 13.4% increase in
block hours, which was partially offset by our jets&rsquo; more efficient fuel burn.&nbsp; Our actual price of fuel, including
taxes, in 2005 and 2004 was 71.2 cents per gallon.&nbsp; Under the capacity purchase agreement and related fuel purchase agreement
with Continental, we incur a fuel price and fuel tax equal to the lower of the actual cost of fuel and fuel tax or the agreed-upon
caps.&nbsp; Beginning in 2003, until the termination of these agreements, caps on fuel and fuel tax are 66.0 cents and 5.2 cents
per gallon, respectively.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately $21.2 million of
the increase in maintenance, materials and repairs during 2005 was due to a 13.7% increase in flight hours related to our
power-by-the-hour contracts.&nbsp; Our overall maintenance, materials and repair costs per flight hour increased by approximately
4.0% to support the continuing growth and aging of our fleet.&nbsp; Since approximately 70% of our maintenance, materials and
repairs cost in 2005 consisted of power-by-the-hour expenses, we believe that these agreements, coupled with our ongoing
maintenance program, reduce the likelihood of unexpected maintenance expense during the aircraft lease term.&nbsp; We expect our
future maintenance, materials and repair expenses, adjusted for volume and further fleet aging, to mirror our current cost
structure.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The increase in other rentals and
landing fees during 2005 was primarily due to a $10.5 million increase in landing fees caused by an 11.2% increase in landing
weights and 3.0% increase in rates per landing weight mostly due to higher rates at Continental&rsquo;s hubs.&nbsp; In addition,
our facility rent increased by approximately $5.5 million primarily as a result of rate increases at various stations and
maintenance facilities.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ground handling and outside
services decreased in 2005 because as part of the 2005 annual rate resetting process and as a result of Continental&rsquo;s
cost-saving initiatives, the costs for Continental to provide us with certain services currently classified as outside services
(such as technology infrastructure and other services) and ground handling were reduced by approximately $53.0 million for the year
ended December 31, 2005.&nbsp; As these are fully reconciled costs, our operating income for 2005 was reduced by approximately $5.3
million as a result of these cost reductions.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" color="black" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately $2.0
million of the increase in depreciation was due to additional obsolescence expense recorded in 2005 to reduce the value of various
aircraft spare parts to net realizable value.&nbsp; As depreciation is a fully reconciled cost under the capacity purchase
agreement, the impact on pre-tax income was immaterial.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The decrease in other operating
expenses for the year ended December 31, 2005 resulted primarily from:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">

</td>

</td>

increased flight operations.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Nonoperating
Expenses</i></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Our interest
expense is primarily related to our senior convertible notes, note payable to Continental and loan agreement with EDC.&nbsp;
Interest expense related to these long-term debts decreased in 2005 by approximately $1.1 million as a result of an $81.3 million
reduction in our note payable to Continental and a $0.9 million reduction in our loan agreement with EDC.&nbsp; In addition, we
retired Airlines&rsquo; Series A Preferred Stock in April 2005.&nbsp; Our interest income increased by approximately $4.6 million
as a result of a two-point increase in our average returns from our investments despite a lower average cash and short-term
investment balance of approximately $208.9 million in 2005.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Comparison of 2004 to
2003</i></font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Operating
Revenue</i></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our operating income in 2004
reflected a 13.6% operating margin, compared with an operating margin of 13.9% in 2003.&nbsp; The 2004 and 2003 operating margins
included the benefits of cost savings and $11.5 million and $12.9 million in performance incentive payments under our capacity
purchase agreement, respectively.&nbsp; We earn incentive payments primarily by achieving a controllable completion factor which
was 99.9% and 99.8% in 2004 and 2003, respectively, versus a historical benchmark factor of 98.9% and 98.5% for the same
periods.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of cost savings from
maintenance, materials and repairs and passenger servicing expenses in 2004 and 2003, our prevailing margin (before reconciliation
payments) exceeded 11.5%; consequently, we made reconciliation payments to Continental totaling $61.0 million and $30.1 million in
2004 and 2003, respectively.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <i>Operating
Expenses</i></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As our operations have grown, our
direct labor groups such as pilots, flight attendants, mechanics, dispatchers and customer service agents have increased
proportionally.&nbsp; This larger work force and increases in wage rates under some of our collective bargaining agreements
increased our wages, salaries and related costs by $20.3 million in 2004.&nbsp; Increases related to our non-direct labor groups
such as clerical and management positions were approximately $4.2 million in 2004.&nbsp; We also incurred approximately $8.1
million in additional employee benefit costs in 2004 due to increases in medical benefit costs, workers&rsquo; compensation,
payroll taxes and 401 (k) expenses.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<font size="2" face="Arial"><br clear="all" />
</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The increase in our aircraft fuel
expense in 2004 was mainly due to a 21.8% increase in fuel consumption and a 0.2% increase in fuel price and related taxes over
2003.&nbsp; Consumption rose primarily due to a 23.0% increase in block hours, which was partially offset by our jets&rsquo; more
efficient fuel burn.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately $29.3 million of
the increase in maintenance, materials and repairs during 2004 was due to a 21.5% increase in flight hours and a 14.0% increase in
rate-per-flight-hour related to our power-by-the-hour contracts.&nbsp; The rate-per-flight-hour increase was mainly attributed to a
higher number of power-by-the-hour contracts in place during 2004.&nbsp; For the year ended December 31, 2004, approximately 10
points more of our maintenance, materials and repairs cost consisted of power&ndash;by-the-hour expense versus the same period in
2003.&nbsp; As a result of the increased coverage under our power-by-the-hour contracts, our airframe, avionics and engine
component repair and replacement costs decreased by approximately $7.0 million.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The decrease in other rentals and
landing fees in 2004 was primarily due to a $21.3 million decrease in our terminal facility rents at Continentals&rsquo; hub
stations as a result of an amendment to our master facility and ground handling agreement in November 2003.&nbsp; This decrease was
partially offset by higher facility rent in non-hub stations of approximately $2.2 million, as the number of stations in which we
operate increased.&nbsp; In addition, our landing fees in 2004 increased by $10.7 million as a result of a 15.0% increase in
landing weights and an 8.4% increase in landing fee rates.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The increase in other operating
expenses was mainly due to the following:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

</td>
<td valign="top">

increased flight operations and flight training activities;</font></p>
</td>

for security fees under the Emergency Wartime Supplemental Appropriation Act of 2003 in 2004; and</font></p>

</td>

2004.</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nonoperating
Expenses</font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></i></p>

<p><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></i> Since we issued our
senior convertible notes in August 2003 and drew on&nbsp; a loan facility from EDC in May and September 2003, our interest expense
increased by $4.2 million in 2004 compared to 2003.&nbsp; This was partially offset by a $2.3 million decrease in interest expense
related to our note payable to Continental.&nbsp; Furthermore, our interest income increased by $1.6 million as a result of a 0.3
point increase in our return from our investments and higher average cash and short-term investment balance of approximately $71.4
million in 2004 as compared to 2003.</p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><b><i><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Future
Costs</font></i></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We remain committed to providing
competitively priced service by controlling our costs; however, we believe that our costs may still increase in the future due
to:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top">

</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in wages, salaries and related fringe benefit costs, as described above;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in the costs of materials and outside services;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">changes in governmental regulations, insurance and taxes affecting air transportation and the costs
charged for airport access, including new security requirements;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">the aging of our fleet;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<div align="center"><font size="3" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />

</font>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">

<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">higher aircraft ownership costs as new aircraft are delivered, to the extent these aircraft are not
covered by the capacity purchase agreement or if Continental were to declare bankruptcy or otherwise default under the current
financing arrangements;</font></p>
</td>

and other agreement, which may be renegotiated; or</font></p>

</td>

</td>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In the short-term, higher costs
related to the capacity purchase agreement would generate higher revenues; however, in the long-run, failure to control our costs
would prevent us from remaining competitive and limit our opportunities to attract additional partners or to take advantage of
opportunities as they present themselves.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition, we believe future
costs will increase as we explore opportunities to leverage our operational expertise and analyze strategic investments in the air
transportation sectors both in the U.S. and abroad.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><a name="liquidity"></a><b><font size="2" face="Arial">Liquidity and Capital Commitments</font></b></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Sources and Uses of
Cash</i></b></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Our primary source of liquidity
is cash flow provided from our operations.&nbsp; For the years ended December 31, 2005 and 2004, our operations provided $130.6
million and $153.6 million, respectively, in cash flow.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005 and 2004, we also had $9.2 million and $6.3
million of restricted cash, respectively, which is used as collateral for our workers&rsquo; compensation
coverage.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005 and 2004, we spent $21.1
million and $38.9 million, respectively, on flight and ground equipment to support our fleet deliveries and the increase in our
flight schedules under our capacity purchase agreement with Continental.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, we made the following
cash investments:</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<div align="center">
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="672">
<tr>
<td valign="top"></td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">In March 2005, we purchased 50% minus one share of JetX Aviation for $0.9 million.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">
<p align="right"><font size="2" face="Arial">&bull;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td valign="top">
<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>
<td valign="top">

</td>
<td valign="top">

$5.8 million.&nbsp; $4.9 million of the purchase price was recorded as building, land and related improvements and the balance was
treated as our non-controlling investment.&nbsp;</font></p>
</td>

</td>

</table>
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, we also began
construction of an aircraft painting facility in Mexico.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, the cost of this facility was approximately
$5.0 million.&nbsp; The total cost of the facility is expected to be $8.7 million, and we expect to complete it during the second
quarter of 2006.&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Additionally, we negotiated the
sale of eight engines to Rolls Royce and, in exchange, entered into seven new engine leases with a Rolls Royce subsidiary in
December 2005.&nbsp; Net proceeds received for this transaction were $15.3 million, which we reported as cash flow from financing
activities.&nbsp; See detailed discussion below in &ldquo;&mdash;Purchase Commitments&rdquo;.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Long-term
Debt</i>.</b>&nbsp; We did not enter into any new financing transactions in 2005.&nbsp; We made the quarterly principal and
interest payments on our note payable to Continental to the extent required on March 31, June 30, September 30 and December 31,
2005, net of prepayments made in prior periods.&nbsp; These payments, totaled $84.7 million, of which $81.3 million related to
principal.&nbsp; In September 2004, we made a voluntary prepayment totaling $27.0 million, which reduced our required quarterly
principal and interest payment on March 31, 2005.&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, the balance on our note payable to Continental was
$17.5 million.&nbsp; We plan to pay off this obligation in March 2006.</font></p>

<div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial"></font>
<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="#3366ff" align="center" />
</div>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"><a href="#TOC">Table of Contents</a></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, we made principal and
interest payments in the amount of $1.6 million on our loan agreement with EDC, of which $0.9 million related to principal.&nbsp;
As of December 31, 2005, the balance on this loan agreement was $15.3 million.&nbsp; In addition, we made required dividend and
interest payments in 2005 on Airlines&rsquo; Series A Preferred Stock and our 4.25% senior convertible notes due 2023 totaling $6.0
million.&nbsp; We redeemed the Series A Preferred Stock in April 2005, the earliest date on which it was callable by us.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Capital
Leases.</i></b>&nbsp; As of December 31, 2005, we had approximately $1.8 million (including current maturities) of capital lease
obligations.&nbsp; In 2005, we made $1.0 million total payments related to our capital leases, of which $0.8 million related to
principal.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Other than the financing
activities described above, we do not have any other sources of long-term borrowings or available lines of credit.&nbsp;
Additionally, there is no covenant under any of our long-term debt agreements that restrict our ability to undertake additional
debt or equity financing.&nbsp; If we default on our payment obligations under the note payable to or under our aircraft subleases
with Continental, in addition to any other remedies it may have, Continental can elect to reduce its payments to us under the
capacity purchase agreement by the amount of the defaulted payment.&nbsp; If Continental defaults on the payment obligations it has
to us under our capacity purchase and other agreements, then in addition to any other remedies we may have, we can offset the
amount of the defaulted payment against amounts we owe to Continental under the note.&nbsp; In addition, Continental or we can
reduce any payments to the other party under the capacity purchase agreement in an amount corresponding to any defaulted payments
by the other party under the foregoing obligations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; See Item 8.&nbsp;
&ldquo;Financial Statements and Supplementary Data &ndash;Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements &ndash;Note 5,&rdquo;
&ldquo;&ndash; Note 6,&rdquo; &ldquo;&ndash;Note 7&rdquo; and &ldquo;&ndash;Note 8&rdquo; for detailed descriptions of these
long-term debts and obligations.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b><i>Securities Repurchase
Program.</i></b>&nbsp; In July 2005, our board of directors authorized the expenditure of up to $30 million to repurchase shares of
our common stock.&nbsp; Since the inception of the program, we have purchased 590,800 shares of our common stock at an average cost
per share of $9.55.&nbsp; In February 2006, the board authorized the inclusion of our 4.25% convertible notes due 2023 within the
previously announced $30 million program.</font></p>

<p><font size="2" face="Arial"></font></p>
